Yes.

253
00:21:34,600 --> 00:21:38,559
I'm really sorry.
This isn't a good time.

254
00:21:39,480 --> 00:21:41,516
We've had to medicate
your husband.

255
00:21:41,600 --> 00:21:44,910
So perhaps you could
come back tomorrow.

256
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:48,515
I don't mind if he's asleep.
I'd just like to see him.

257
00:21:50,440 --> 00:21:53,398
I don't think
that's a good idea.

258
00:21:54,600 --> 00:21:57,637
Your husband is going through
a temporary depression.

259
00:21:59,400 --> 00:22:01,391
But I'd still like
to see him.

260
00:22:03,200 --> 00:22:05,919
I'm so sorry. He doesn't
want to see you.

261
00:22:10,760 --> 00:22:12,239
Excuse me.

262
00:22:16,840 --> 00:22:19,035
There we are.
Tid.

263
00:22:19,120 --> 00:22:20,656
I can manage from now on.
(BABY FUSSING)

264
00:22:20,680 --> 00:22:22,591
It's not fair to
ask you to do this.

265
00:22:22,680 --> 00:22:24,591
Well, I don't see why not.
All right.

266
00:22:24,680 --> 00:22:27,353
I looked after you when you
were a baby, didn't I?

267
00:22:30,440 --> 00:22:33,159
The thing is, we're not
very well off, I'm afraid.

268
00:22:34,160 --> 00:22:37,072
We've got some savings,
but there's not a lot coming in.

269
00:22:37,160 --> 00:22:38,957
Oh, you don't need to
worry about that.

270
00:22:39,040 --> 00:22:40,951
Your family's
my family, really.

271
00:22:42,080 --> 00:22:44,116
It's nice to be back.
Come on.

272
00:22:44,200 --> 00:22:46,919
That's it.
Come on, little man.

273
00:22:47,000 --> 00:22:49,753
Off we go. Come on.

274
00:22:58,480 --> 00:23:00,471
DAVID: Ma?

275
00:23:00,560 --> 00:23:02,676
Moo?

276
00:23:02,800 --> 00:23:03,994
Me?

277
00:23:04,080 --> 00:23:06,275
Me. He said "me."

278
00:23:10,640 --> 00:23:11,675
Eh.

279
00:23:11,760 --> 00:23:13,910
"Eh." "Get."
Is the first word "get"?

280
00:23:15,200 --> 00:23:16,519
Or "let"?

281
00:23:18,800 --> 00:23:19,800
"Let me lie"?

282
00:23:21,720 --> 00:23:23,756
Well, he is lying.

283
00:23:23,880 --> 00:23:26,997
Sorry, Robin, you must think
we're awful chumps.

284
00:23:28,560 --> 00:23:35,238
Let me die.

285
00:23:39,360 --> 00:23:40,360
"Let me die."

286
00:23:43,440 --> 00:23:44,440
DAVID: Talking to Robin

287
00:23:44,520 --> 00:23:46,720
was rather like playing one
of those ghastly party games

288
00:23:46,760 --> 00:23:48,751
where you don't know
the rules.

289
00:23:48,840 --> 00:23:51,195
It's very clever of you to get
him to say anything at all.

290
00:23:51,280 --> 00:23:53,271
Well, what he said was...

291
00:23:55,840 --> 00:23:57,831
What he said was,
"Let me die."

292
00:24:01,360 --> 00:24:03,954
Well, we can't, can we?

293
00:24:04,040 --> 00:24:05,576
You mean we can't even
think of such a thing

294
00:24:05,600 --> 00:24:07,079
or we wouldn't know
how to do it?

295
00:24:07,160 --> 00:24:08,229
Both, I suppose.

296
00:24:08,320 --> 00:24:09,496
Well, it makes
no odds, really.

297
00:24:09,520 --> 00:24:12,796
I had a sort of word with the consultant,
and he wouldn't hear of it.

298
00:24:12,880 --> 00:24:14,871
It's not what they do.

299
00:24:14,960 --> 00:24:16,336
It's not a good way
to go, apparently.

300
00:24:16,360 --> 00:24:17,793
It's several minutes
of agony.

301
00:24:17,880 --> 00:24:19,871
No. No, I don't
want that.

302
00:24:19,960 --> 00:24:21,359
No, of course not.

303
00:24:24,320 --> 00:24:26,436
You do have a life,
too, you know.

304
00:24:26,520 --> 00:24:28,556
You are allowed to
think of yourself.

305
00:24:32,240 --> 00:24:34,231
DR. ENTWISTLE: Chin up.
We're doing very well.

306
00:24:41,160 --> 00:24:44,391
Well, Mrs. Cavendish, we do
have some progress to report.

307
00:24:44,480 --> 00:24:45,629
Progress?

308
00:24:45,720 --> 00:24:47,915
We're learning to swallow again.

309
00:24:49,080 --> 00:24:50,308
We are?

310
00:24:50,400 --> 00:24:52,630
It's more significant
than it sounds.

311
00:24:52,760 --> 00:24:56,753
At present, we have an inflated
cuff round our tracheotomy tube

312
00:24:56,840 --> 00:24:59,718
to stop food and drink
going down our windpipe.

313
00:25:00,360 --> 00:25:01,918
If we can swallow again,

314
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:04,992
the cuff can be removed,
and air can get to the larynx.

315
00:25:05,080 --> 00:25:07,071
Then we'll be able
to talk again.

316
00:25:07,920 --> 00:25:10,309
DIANA: Might there be
other progress, too?

317
00:25:10,400 --> 00:25:13,278
DR. ENTWISTLE: This is about as good
as it's going to get, I'm afraid.

318
00:25:14,240 --> 00:25:16,231
How are we this morning?

319
00:25:18,840 --> 00:25:21,673
We wish we were dead.
Good, good.

320
00:25:21,760 --> 00:25:23,591
Good morning to you, Paddy.

321
00:25:35,400 --> 00:25:37,391
He couldn't go on
having no name,

322
00:25:40,200 --> 00:25:42,191
so I decided to
call him Jonathan.

323
00:25:46,240 --> 00:25:48,231
I hope that's all right.

324
00:25:52,880 --> 00:25:54,472
DIANA: He never
even looks at him.

325
00:25:56,760 --> 00:25:58,751
He can't bear to
even look at him.

326
00:26:00,160 --> 00:26:01,559
You don't know that.

327
00:26:02,960 --> 00:26:04,473
Yes, I do.

328
00:26:05,560 --> 00:26:08,996
I do. I know everything
he's thinking.

329
00:26:11,160 --> 00:26:13,993
Every time I come here,
I hope he'll have changed.

330
00:26:14,080 --> 00:26:15,308
NURSE MARGARET:
Nearly there.

331
00:26:15,400 --> 00:26:17,550
DIANA: But he can't bear to
look at his own son.

332
00:26:17,680 --> 00:26:19,033
Well done.

333
00:26:50,920 --> 00:26:54,708
CHAPLAIN: An old priest
I knew once, a very holy man,

334
00:26:56,040 --> 00:26:58,190
he used to say,

335
00:26:58,280 --> 00:27:02,114
"Those that God loves most,
He allows to suffer most."

336
00:27:04,800 --> 00:27:06,791
We can't know the mind of God,

337
00:27:06,880 --> 00:27:10,156
but we can be sure
that whatever happens to us

338
00:27:11,120 --> 00:27:13,190
is somehow part of His plan.

339
00:27:16,080 --> 00:27:17,957
(MUMBLES)

340
00:27:19,480 --> 00:27:20,959
I'm sorry. I didn't get that.

341
00:27:22,360 --> 00:27:23,839
Move closer.

342
00:27:23,920 --> 00:27:25,911
Closer. Yes, of course.

343
00:27:28,280 --> 00:27:29,713
(SPITS)
(GASPS)

344
00:27:30,520 --> 00:27:34,069
Yes, well...
I'll be on my way.

345
00:27:38,160 --> 00:27:41,038
I'm thinking
you're not a believer.

346
00:27:42,760 --> 00:27:44,751
Believer in what?

347
00:27:47,240 --> 00:27:48,798
God's a joke.

348
00:27:49,280 --> 00:27:51,316
Hmm. No, pal.

349
00:27:51,440 --> 00:27:53,431
God's a joker.

350
00:27:55,520 --> 00:27:58,512
Look at the pig's mickey
he's made of you and me.

351
00:27:58,600 --> 00:28:00,079
(PADDY WHEEZES)

352
00:28:04,000 --> 00:28:05,991
How do you live like this?

353
00:28:07,760 --> 00:28:10,035
Ah... You get used to it.

354
00:28:10,120 --> 00:28:12,793
What if I don't?

355
00:28:12,920 --> 00:28:15,036
Well, there's always
a way out.

356
00:28:15,120 --> 00:28:16,758
Like Pete there got out.

357
00:28:19,440 --> 00:28:22,034
In his own private box.

358
00:28:30,360 --> 00:28:32,749
(RESPIRATOR HISSING)

359
00:28:46,320 --> 00:28:47,719
DIANA: Robin.

360
00:28:57,640 --> 00:28:59,119
Robin. (LAUGHS)

361
00:29:09,000 --> 00:29:10,479
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

362
00:29:10,600 --> 00:29:11,828
DIANA: (WHISPERS) Robin.

363
00:29:20,520 --> 00:29:22,511
ROBIN: Why do you
keep on coming here?

364
00:29:25,840 --> 00:29:27,831
I don't really know.

365
00:29:30,480 --> 00:29:32,471
I'm no use to you.

366
00:29:37,200 --> 00:29:39,350
You really must
leave me here to rot now.

367
00:29:43,880 --> 00:29:45,871
Well, it wouldn't look
very good.

368
00:29:49,800 --> 00:29:52,997
And apparently,
I love you.

369
00:29:54,120 --> 00:29:57,874
You don't love this.
You can't love this.

370
00:29:58,880 --> 00:30:00,598
Apparently, I can.

371
00:30:01,360 --> 00:30:03,351
Well, I don't
want you to.

372
00:30:04,800 --> 00:30:06,791
Don't you understand that?

373
00:30:10,560 --> 00:30:11,879
Makes it harder for me.

374
00:30:13,400 --> 00:30:15,391
Yes, I can see that.

375
00:30:18,080 --> 00:30:21,072
You'd rather just
pack it in, I know.

376
00:30:21,680 --> 00:30:24,069
And bloody machine

377
00:30:27,200 --> 00:30:29,509
that keeps on
breathing for me.

378
00:30:31,360 --> 00:30:32,679
So it looks

379
00:30:32,760 --> 00:30:36,594
as if you're going to have to stick
around for a while, doesn't it?

380
00:30:40,080 --> 00:30:41,559
I'm sorry to say.

381
00:30:41,640 --> 00:30:43,517
I'm not sorry.

382
00:30:45,920 --> 00:30:48,070
I want Jonathan
to know you.

383
00:30:49,760 --> 00:30:54,754
And maybe... Maybe I can make
life a little better for you.

384
00:30:57,720 --> 00:30:59,631
Don't want your duty.

385
00:31:02,560 --> 00:31:03,879
Yes, all right.

386
00:31:03,960 --> 00:31:07,589
All right. All right.
We know all about that.

387
00:31:09,360 --> 00:31:11,828
Everything's as bad
as it could possibly be.

388
00:31:13,440 --> 00:31:15,556
But I can't go on
coming in here

389
00:31:15,640 --> 00:31:18,200
and have you say
that you wish you were dead.

390
00:31:20,200 --> 00:31:23,192
Because you're not dead,
and that's that.

391
00:31:26,440 --> 00:31:27,793
Robin.

392
00:31:31,760 --> 00:31:33,159
Robin.

393
00:31:36,800 --> 00:31:38,376
Come on, there must be
something I can do

394
00:31:38,400 --> 00:31:40,630
to make things
more bearable.

395
00:31:47,440 --> 00:31:49,431
Get me out of here.

396
00:31:58,120 --> 00:32:01,749
I'm afraid it's out of
the question. I'm sorry.

397
00:32:01,840 --> 00:32:03,432
DIANA: Well,
has anyone ever tried?

398
00:32:03,520 --> 00:32:04,919
(SIGHS)

399
00:32:07,960 --> 00:32:10,918
No one with your husband's
degree of disability

400
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:12,558
anywhere in the world

401
00:32:12,640 --> 00:32:14,995
exists outside a hospital.

402
00:32:15,720 --> 00:32:17,233
(SIGHS)

403
00:32:18,160 --> 00:32:21,232
But I've watched
what the nurses do,

404
00:32:21,320 --> 00:32:23,834
and if we had
a ventilator at home,

405
00:32:23,960 --> 00:32:26,428
I just don't see
why it wouldn't work.

406
00:32:29,800 --> 00:32:31,631
Allow me to explain.

407
00:32:31,760 --> 00:32:36,629
Your husband is only alive because
a machine is breathing for him.

408
00:32:36,720 --> 00:32:39,280
If that machine
should fail,

409
00:32:39,360 --> 00:32:42,352
in under two minutes,
your husband would be dead.

410
00:32:44,160 --> 00:32:46,196
Forgive me
if I speak plainly.

411
00:32:47,200 --> 00:32:49,191
Do I make myself clear?

412
00:32:51,920 --> 00:32:55,674
I'll be sad to go, of course,
after all these years.

413
00:32:56,720 --> 00:33:01,316
But since Muriel died, I can't
seem to get on top of things.

414
00:33:01,400 --> 00:33:02,435
Hmm.

415
00:33:02,520 --> 00:33:06,069
Things can run away
from you, you know.

416
00:33:06,160 --> 00:33:07,388
Yes.

417
00:33:08,640 --> 00:33:10,835
It's a lot of work.
Is the roof sound?

418
00:33:12,480 --> 00:33:14,118
Some of it.

419
00:33:14,960 --> 00:33:17,235
DIANA: Why are so many of
the windows bricked up?

420
00:33:17,320 --> 00:33:20,073
Ah. Oh, yes,
those are my rooms.

421
00:33:22,040 --> 00:33:26,079
Muriel said it saved such a
lot on the heating bills.

422
00:33:26,160 --> 00:33:27,309
Did she?

423
00:33:29,200 --> 00:33:31,395
Well, it's a lot of work,
but it might do.

424
00:33:32,200 --> 00:33:37,593
The thing is,
I haven't got £12,000,

425
00:33:37,680 --> 00:33:39,830
or anywhere
near that, really.

426
00:33:44,280 --> 00:33:47,829
I'd take 11,
or even 10.

427
00:33:48,880 --> 00:33:50,871
All I can manage is seven.

428
00:33:53,960 --> 00:33:55,951
Seven?
Cash.

429
00:33:57,160 --> 00:33:59,310
And then you'd be
rid of the place forever.

430
00:34:00,120 --> 00:34:01,758
And Muriel.

431
00:34:03,280 --> 00:34:04,759
(MAN CHUCKLES)

432
00:34:04,840 --> 00:34:07,479
Yes.
Really?

433
00:34:07,560 --> 00:34:09,232
Yes. Yes.
Oh!

434
00:34:13,840 --> 00:34:15,296
NURSE MARGARET: And how are
you this morning, Robin?

435
00:34:15,320 --> 00:34:16,389
Did you sleep well?

436
00:34:16,480 --> 00:34:18,471
You're looking good.

437
00:34:20,400 --> 00:34:22,118
Good morning, darling.

438
00:34:22,200 --> 00:34:23,599
Morning, Margaret.

439
00:34:23,680 --> 00:34:25,033
Almost done,
Mrs. Cavendish.

440
00:34:34,280 --> 00:34:35,633
Is that something
I could do?

441
00:34:37,600 --> 00:34:38,600
I don't see why not.

442
00:34:40,040 --> 00:34:42,031
It's just like
a Hoover, really.

443
00:34:43,280 --> 00:34:44,429
Could I try?

444
00:34:47,240 --> 00:34:48,275
Here.

445
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:52,000
Just...

446
00:34:52,040 --> 00:34:53,109
Right.

447
00:34:54,520 --> 00:34:56,351
Good.

448
00:34:56,480 --> 00:34:57,913
Oh, no, sorry.

449
00:34:58,000 --> 00:34:59,479
Let me.
Let me take it.

450
00:35:03,440 --> 00:35:06,193
Once I got used to it,
I think I could manage.

451
00:35:07,320 --> 00:35:09,515
Why would you want
to manage, Mrs. Cavendish?

452
00:35:11,360 --> 00:35:13,590
Dr. Khan. Robin and I,

453
00:35:13,680 --> 00:35:16,752
we wanted to ask you a question.
Didn't we, Robin?

454
00:35:18,600 --> 00:35:22,036
Can machines like that ventilator
only work in hospitals?

455
00:35:23,000 --> 00:35:25,275
DR. KHAN: Well, it's just
a machine, you know.

456
00:35:25,360 --> 00:35:27,510
You plug it in,
and it goes.

457
00:35:28,240 --> 00:35:29,559
Why do you ask?

458
00:35:30,800 --> 00:35:32,631
Robin's going to
leave the hospital.

459
00:35:40,520 --> 00:35:42,750
Do you have any idea
of the risks?

460
00:35:42,840 --> 00:35:45,638
Yes. Yes, I do.

461
00:35:45,720 --> 00:35:47,711
The risk is that
he might die.

462
00:35:51,720 --> 00:35:53,153
Robin.

463
00:35:59,480 --> 00:36:01,675
I either go on living here,

464
00:36:05,760 --> 00:36:08,069
or leave here
and possibly die.

465
00:36:09,320 --> 00:36:10,594
Yes.

466
00:36:13,160 --> 00:36:15,151
Well, what are we
waiting for?

467
00:36:19,760 --> 00:36:21,990
Up, up.
I thought we were going down.

468
00:36:22,080 --> 00:36:25,436
No, lift your end up
so we can get the bed down.

469
00:36:25,560 --> 00:36:26,959
Very heavy.

470
00:36:28,440 --> 00:36:30,112
(DAVID GRUNTING)

471
00:36:32,600 --> 00:36:33,953
Left, left.

472
00:36:34,040 --> 00:36:35,519
I am going left.

473
00:36:35,600 --> 00:36:38,160
Sorry. Your right.

474
00:36:41,960 --> 00:36:44,110
(DAVID CONTINUES GRUNTING)

475
00:36:50,080 --> 00:36:52,992
So, Robin goes in this bed?

476
00:36:53,080 --> 00:36:54,308
Yeah.

477
00:36:54,440 --> 00:36:57,079
And then Diana's bed
goes next to it?

478
00:36:57,160 --> 00:36:58,559
That's what she wants, yeah.

479
00:37:00,160 --> 00:37:02,469
But surely Robin will have
a nurse when he...

480
00:37:02,560 --> 00:37:04,994
No nurse. Just Diana.

481
00:37:05,760 --> 00:37:08,479
I mean, well...

482
00:37:09,840 --> 00:37:12,274
She can't be with him every
minute of the day and night.

483
00:37:12,360 --> 00:37:13,873
She's got to pee,
hasn't she?

484
00:37:14,000 --> 00:37:15,035
She's got me.

485
00:37:18,480 --> 00:37:22,393
PADDY: £5 says
you'll never make it.

486
00:37:24,440 --> 00:37:26,431
ROBIN: And what do I get
if I do?

487
00:37:27,760 --> 00:37:30,274
You get £5, you t'ick.

488
00:37:33,120 --> 00:37:34,872
You're on.

489
00:37:39,880 --> 00:37:41,518
DR. KHAN: Ready?

490
00:37:48,160 --> 00:37:51,311
So long, chaps. So long.
PADDY: Best of luck, Robin.

491
00:37:52,800 --> 00:37:56,156
So long, Paddy.
I'll be back for my fiver.

492
00:37:59,280 --> 00:38:00,679
(SNORING)

493
00:38:02,400 --> 00:38:04,470
I'll miss you, pal.

494
00:38:31,960 --> 00:38:33,800
DR. ENTWISTLE: Where do you
think you're going?

495
00:38:35,280 --> 00:38:36,793
We're taking
my husband home.

496
00:38:36,880 --> 00:38:38,916
You don't have my permission.

497
00:38:39,000 --> 00:38:42,310
Is this a prison?
Am I your prisoner?

498
00:38:43,200 --> 00:38:44,679
What do you think
you're doing?

499
00:38:45,440 --> 00:38:47,192
It is the patient's
own wish, sir.

500
00:38:47,280 --> 00:38:49,032
He's fully apprised
of the risks.

501
00:38:49,120 --> 00:38:50,997
Take him back to
the ward at once.

502
00:38:51,080 --> 00:38:53,071
ROBIN: Diana,
call the police.

503
00:38:53,160 --> 00:38:56,072
Tell them I'm being
held against my will.

504
00:38:56,160 --> 00:38:59,550
I'm sorry?
What did you say?

505
00:38:59,640 --> 00:39:03,792
You have no right to...
To keep me in this place.

506
00:39:09,440 --> 00:39:11,431
Of course. Be my guest.

507
00:39:12,280 --> 00:39:14,316
ROBIN: Let's go.
Do as you please.

508
00:39:18,440 --> 00:39:20,431
You'll be dead in two weeks.

509
00:39:24,040 --> 00:39:25,553
Ready?
Yes.

510
00:39:27,200 --> 00:39:28,758
Right, bag going on.

511
00:39:30,080 --> 00:39:31,433
All right.

512
00:39:34,280 --> 00:39:35,315
How's he coping?

513
00:39:35,400 --> 00:39:36,400
DIANA: So far, so good.

514
00:39:36,480 --> 00:39:38,038
Right, ready to move?

515
00:39:38,120 --> 00:39:39,792
DRIVER: Lift, lift.
COLIN: Got it.

516
00:39:40,680 --> 00:39:41,776
BLOGGS: Are you
all right, Diana?

517
00:39:41,800 --> 00:39:43,950
DIANA: Yes.
Okay, gently put him down.

518
00:39:45,000 --> 00:39:47,434
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

519
00:39:49,640 --> 00:39:50,959
And up again.

520
00:40:08,480 --> 00:40:11,153
BLOGGS: Okay. Okay.

521
00:40:12,680 --> 00:40:15,114
TID: Come on. Let's clear the way.
Clear the way.

522
00:40:18,520 --> 00:40:20,158
One, two, three. Lift.
Here we go.

523
00:40:21,560 --> 00:40:23,336
DRIVER: Keep him level.
COLIN: All right, Robin?

524
00:40:23,360 --> 00:40:24,554
DRIVER: Easy.

525
00:40:34,960 --> 00:40:36,816
DIANA: All right, all right. Gently, gently.
TID: You're clear.

526
00:40:36,840 --> 00:40:39,832
DIANA: We need to get him on the
bed over there, so turn him round.

527
00:40:39,920 --> 00:40:42,354
All right, all right.
Yeah, just to the left.

528
00:40:44,520 --> 00:40:46,715
Uh... Right, yes, that goes
on that table there,

529
00:40:46,840 --> 00:40:48,720
and the cable needs to be
to the left-hand side.

530
00:40:48,800 --> 00:40:51,189
Just leave it there.
Sorry, darling.

531
00:40:51,280 --> 00:40:52,280
Harry.
No, no, Bengy.

532
00:40:52,360 --> 00:40:53,952
Could you come here?
Bengy, get down.

533
00:40:54,040 --> 00:40:56,190
Bengy.
Bengy, off the bed.

534
00:40:56,280 --> 00:40:57,633
You need to do
what I'm doing.

535
00:40:57,720 --> 00:40:59,278
He'll tell you.
Hold on to the cable.

536
00:40:59,360 --> 00:41:00,634
Got it, got it, got it.

537
00:41:00,720 --> 00:41:02,280
He'll tell you if
you're going too fast.

538
00:41:02,320 --> 00:41:04,276
All right, Col, we need
to get him on the bed.

539
00:41:05,720 --> 00:41:08,029
One, two, three. Lift.

540
00:41:08,120 --> 00:41:09,473
There we go.

541
00:41:09,560 --> 00:41:11,790
HARRY: Got him.
It's okay. Okay.

542
00:41:11,880 --> 00:41:13,757
(GRUNTS) Right. Right.

543
00:41:14,120 --> 00:41:15,553
TID: Bengy, off you go.

544
00:41:16,040 --> 00:41:17,758
Just take
your shoes off, Robin.

545
00:41:17,840 --> 00:41:19,910
COLIN: Is it on?
Right...

546
00:41:20,000 --> 00:41:22,176
We're going to change your tubes
right now, darling. Ready, Harry?

547
00:41:22,200 --> 00:41:23,713
I've got your hand, Robin.

548
00:41:25,720 --> 00:41:26,720
All right.

549
00:41:27,400 --> 00:41:28,435
(RESPIRATOR STARTING)

550
00:41:28,520 --> 00:41:29,839
DIANA: It's on.

551
00:41:32,920 --> 00:41:34,239
You all right, darling?

552
00:41:56,520 --> 00:41:57,873
Yes, I think I am.

553
00:41:57,960 --> 00:42:00,679
(ALL LAUGH IN RELIEF)

554
00:42:01,680 --> 00:42:03,238
HARRY: Thank God.

555
00:42:03,920 --> 00:42:05,273
(LAUGHS)

556
00:42:05,360 --> 00:42:06,679
Can't believe
it actually works.

557
00:42:06,760 --> 00:42:08,193
Yes, it works.

558
00:42:13,280 --> 00:42:14,349
Could you get Jonathan?

559
00:42:14,440 --> 00:42:16,078
Oh, yes, of course,
my dear.

560
00:42:17,880 --> 00:42:20,952
DIANA: So this is it.
Our new home.

561
00:42:23,800 --> 00:42:25,279
How do you feel?

562
00:42:28,280 --> 00:42:29,838
Much better.

563
00:42:31,640 --> 00:42:33,790
Diana, what happens
if there's a power cut?

564
00:42:33,880 --> 00:42:35,518
You work it
with a hand pump.

565
00:42:36,880 --> 00:42:39,030
It's a nifty bit of kit.
(AIR WHISTLING)

566
00:42:43,160 --> 00:42:44,798
Look who's here.

567
00:42:46,480 --> 00:42:47,708
Hello.

568
00:42:47,800 --> 00:42:49,119
There you go.

569
00:42:50,480 --> 00:42:52,038
Oh...

570
00:42:52,120 --> 00:42:53,917
Look, Jonathan.

571
00:42:55,240 --> 00:42:56,639
It's Daddy.

572
00:43:04,920 --> 00:43:06,592
Hello, Jonathan.

573
00:43:12,480 --> 00:43:14,152
Hello, dear boy.

574
00:43:16,000 --> 00:43:17,000
(BENGY BARKS)
(GASPS)

575
00:43:17,080 --> 00:43:18,798
(ALL LAUGHING)

576
00:43:18,880 --> 00:43:20,598
This is Bengy.

577
00:43:23,360 --> 00:43:25,316
(ROBIN GROWLING)

578
00:44:04,880 --> 00:44:06,871
DIANA: Night, darling.

579
00:44:09,680 --> 00:44:11,671
ROBIN: Good night, my love.

580
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:30,035
(JONATHAN RUNNING)

581
00:44:39,480 --> 00:44:41,914
(RESPIRATOR STOPS)

582
00:44:46,760 --> 00:44:48,193
Diana.

583
00:44:49,280 --> 00:44:50,713
Diana.

584
00:44:51,880 --> 00:44:54,075
(CHOKING) Di. Di.

585
00:44:58,600 --> 00:45:01,160
(CONTINUES CHOKING)

586
00:45:04,560 --> 00:45:06,790
(CLICKING TONGUE)

587
00:45:20,120 --> 00:45:21,155
(BARKS)

588
00:45:21,280 --> 00:45:24,397
Had a bit of a bump, darling?
Oh, no.

589
00:45:24,480 --> 00:45:28,473
What's the matter?
Has Mummy not been playing?

590
00:45:28,560 --> 00:45:31,870
Shall we go and find Daddy?
Where's Daddy hiding? (GASPS)

591
00:45:31,960 --> 00:45:35,316
Where's Daddy? He's in there.
Shall we go and find him?

592
00:45:35,400 --> 00:45:38,631
What's that naughty Daddy doing?
Daddy? (GASPS)

593
00:45:38,720 --> 00:45:40,836
Jonathan, Jonathan.
(SHUSHING)

594
00:45:40,920 --> 00:45:42,319
(SUFFOCATING)
Daddy?

595
00:45:44,840 --> 00:45:46,239
Robin?

596
00:45:47,560 --> 00:45:48,993
Robin?

597
00:45:50,440 --> 00:45:52,078
Oh, my God. Robin?

598
00:45:58,120 --> 00:46:01,510
(RESPIRATOR STARTS)
Robin? Robin? Robin?

599
00:46:03,440 --> 00:46:06,637
Please, please, please.
Robin. Robin.

600
00:46:07,960 --> 00:46:09,598
Oh, my God.

601
00:46:11,520 --> 00:46:13,829
Please. Oh, my God.

602
00:46:14,400 --> 00:46:16,231
(INHALES)
(SIGHS)

603
00:46:24,200 --> 00:46:26,191
That was interesting.

604
00:46:26,360 --> 00:46:27,713
Oh...

605
00:46:29,360 --> 00:46:31,351
Oh, my God.

606
00:46:31,720 --> 00:46:35,679
(UPBEAT JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING)

607
00:46:54,080 --> 00:46:55,308
(BOTTLE POPS)
Ah!

608
00:46:55,400 --> 00:46:57,231
I've saved the best
till last.

609
00:46:57,320 --> 00:47:01,393
This one spent the whole of the
war in my air-raid shelter.

610
00:47:01,480 --> 00:47:02,913
Looks like
a good drop, Teddy.

611
00:47:03,000 --> 00:47:04,149
It is a good drop.

612
00:47:04,240 --> 00:47:06,231
And good wine
deserves good glasses.

613
00:47:06,320 --> 00:47:08,834
This one is for
the lovely Diana.

614
00:47:08,920 --> 00:47:09,920
That's me.

615
00:47:10,040 --> 00:47:11,758
TEDDY: Mary. Katherine.
Bloggs. David.

616
00:47:14,920 --> 00:47:18,151
Biggles.
There we are, darling.

617
00:47:18,240 --> 00:47:19,673
And Tid?

618
00:47:19,760 --> 00:47:21,159
No, no, not for me.

619
00:47:21,240 --> 00:47:22,958
DIANA: Tid only drinks
Dubonnet.

620
00:47:23,040 --> 00:47:25,315
And only on my birthday.

621
00:47:25,400 --> 00:47:26,480
TEDDY: Oh, I almost forgot.

622
00:47:26,520 --> 00:47:28,670
(SHUSHING) He's sleeping.
To Jonathan.

623
00:47:28,760 --> 00:47:31,911
ALL: Happy birthday,
Jonathan.

624
00:47:32,680 --> 00:47:34,159
(PEOPLE LAUGHING)

625
00:47:34,240 --> 00:47:39,872
Yes, I had been wondering what it
might be like to... To get drunk.

626
00:47:40,120 --> 00:47:41,269
(CHUCKLES)

627
00:47:41,360 --> 00:47:43,351
Given that
I'm legless already.

628
00:47:43,440 --> 00:47:47,353
What you have to do with mechanical
devices is stress-test them,

629
00:47:47,440 --> 00:47:49,351
find their
breaking point, so...

630
00:47:49,440 --> 00:47:50,509
It's rather good, Ted.

631
00:47:50,600 --> 00:47:52,113
An interesting
experiment, Teddy.

632
00:47:52,240 --> 00:47:53,355
Robin would die,

633
00:47:53,440 --> 00:47:56,955
but you'd probably be able to
improve your machine probably.

634
00:47:57,080 --> 00:47:59,799
(SCATTERED LAUGHING)
All progress has its price.

635
00:48:00,640 --> 00:48:03,757
It's the power supply that's
usually the weak link.

636
00:48:03,840 --> 00:48:06,354
You know, power can fail.
Power frequently fails.

637
00:48:06,440 --> 00:48:07,839
Oh, do stop it.

638
00:48:07,920 --> 00:48:09,239
I'm only hypothesizing.

639
00:48:09,320 --> 00:48:10,833
He's just doing
his job.

640
00:48:10,920 --> 00:48:12,956
He doesn't have a job.
He's an Oxford professor.

641
00:48:13,040 --> 00:48:15,536
There's nothing to worry about
because it can be worked by hand.

642
00:48:15,560 --> 00:48:17,357
MARY: Well, what about
in the night?

643
00:48:17,440 --> 00:48:19,078
Well, I'm here.

644
00:48:19,160 --> 00:48:20,832
But you have to
sleep some time.

645
00:48:20,960 --> 00:48:22,757
No, she doesn't.
She's a machine.

646
00:48:23,600 --> 00:48:26,239
Well, if Robin needs me, he wakes me.
Don't you, darling?

647
00:48:26,960 --> 00:48:29,918
BLOGGS: Robin makes a noise.
(IMITATES ROBIN)

648
00:48:30,000 --> 00:48:31,149
Like a duck.

649
00:48:31,240 --> 00:48:32,309
That's a chicken, Bloggs.

650
00:48:32,400 --> 00:48:33,958
Can you do
a chicken, Robin?

651
00:48:34,040 --> 00:48:36,076
I hate you so much, Bloggs.

652
00:48:36,200 --> 00:48:37,553
(ALL LAUGH)

653
00:48:37,640 --> 00:48:39,312
(CLICKING TONGUE)

654
00:48:39,400 --> 00:48:40,753
Not much.
Hmm.

655
00:48:42,240 --> 00:48:44,800
Much rather have
a bell or something.

656
00:48:47,240 --> 00:48:48,468
What can you move?

657
00:48:55,360 --> 00:48:57,351
Cover your eyes, everybody.

658
00:48:57,520 --> 00:48:59,590
(ALL LAUGHING)

659
00:48:59,680 --> 00:49:01,591
You can move your head.
Can I?

660
00:49:01,680 --> 00:49:03,398
I've seen you do it.

661
00:49:05,800 --> 00:49:07,279
All right, well, let's...

662
00:49:07,360 --> 00:49:09,351
So move your head.

663
00:49:12,960 --> 00:49:14,800
Oh, yes, I think I can have
some fun with that.

664
00:49:14,840 --> 00:49:16,432
DAVID: Teddy.
Yeah.

665
00:49:18,520 --> 00:49:21,080
(JONATHAN GIGGLING)
(BARKING)

666
00:49:26,200 --> 00:49:27,474
(BELL DINGS)

667
00:49:27,880 --> 00:49:30,110
Oh, that's wonderful.

668
00:49:30,200 --> 00:49:32,555
Darling?
Bottle?

669
00:49:32,640 --> 00:49:34,631
Oh, why not? Yes.
Why not?

670
00:49:35,560 --> 00:49:37,073
But listen.
Mmm-hmm?

671
00:49:39,360 --> 00:49:42,716
You know those Marconi
shares that I bought?

672
00:49:42,800 --> 00:49:44,791
Justin's hot tip, yeah?
Mmm-hmm?

673
00:49:46,800 --> 00:49:48,791
They've almost
doubled in price.

674
00:49:50,400 --> 00:49:51,515
Really?

675
00:49:51,600 --> 00:49:52,635
Yeah.

676
00:49:52,760 --> 00:49:55,558
Crikey. Well, I hope Justin
got something out of it.

677
00:49:57,080 --> 00:50:01,073
Oh, yes, well, he gets a
very agreeable sensation of

678
00:50:04,240 --> 00:50:06,834
helping someone far less
fortunate than himself.

679
00:50:06,920 --> 00:50:07,989
Oh.

680
00:50:09,080 --> 00:50:10,593
Poor Robin.

681
00:50:12,560 --> 00:50:14,551
Paralyzed for life.

682
00:50:14,880 --> 00:50:16,438
Oh...
(CHUCKLES)

683
00:50:16,520 --> 00:50:17,714
Yes.

684
00:50:18,440 --> 00:50:20,749
And his poor wife.
I hear she's a saint.

685
00:50:20,840 --> 00:50:22,353
She is a saint.

686
00:50:22,440 --> 00:50:23,919
A gorgeous saint.

687
00:50:27,280 --> 00:50:28,315
Ah!

688
00:50:58,680 --> 00:51:00,477
(BELL DINGS)

689
00:51:01,960 --> 00:51:03,678
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

690
00:51:04,440 --> 00:51:06,476
Darling, call Teddy Hall,
would you?

691
00:51:08,880 --> 00:51:10,916
I've just had an idea.

692
00:51:11,640 --> 00:51:14,473
(OPERATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

693
00:51:23,360 --> 00:51:24,839
(CRACKLING)
(GROANS)

694
00:51:26,040 --> 00:51:27,040
(SIGHS)

695
00:51:37,600 --> 00:51:39,795
(PATRIOTIC MUSIC PLAYING)

696
00:51:52,200 --> 00:51:53,269
(MEN LAUGHING)

697
00:51:53,360 --> 00:51:55,920
BLOGGS: Robin.
DAVID: Oh, bloody hell.

698
00:51:56,000 --> 00:51:58,070
TEDDY: Ladies and gentlemen,
boys and girls,

699
00:51:58,160 --> 00:52:00,196
may I present
the Cavendish chair!

700
00:52:00,280 --> 00:52:01,474
HARRY: That is amazing.

701
00:52:01,560 --> 00:52:02,754
KATHERINE: Hooray!

702
00:52:02,840 --> 00:52:03,875
TEDDY: Roll up, roll up.

703
00:52:03,960 --> 00:52:05,791
There'll be no
stopping you now, old boy.

704
00:52:05,880 --> 00:52:07,632
TEDDY: Not bad, eh?
It looks terrifying.

705
00:52:07,720 --> 00:52:09,278
What if it breaks?

706
00:52:09,360 --> 00:52:10,793
ROBIN: Unbelievable, Teddy.

707
00:52:10,880 --> 00:52:13,917
HARRY: Left, left, left!
(BARKING)

708
00:52:14,000 --> 00:52:15,399
We've lost the dog. Bengy.

709
00:52:15,480 --> 00:52:16,993
Robin, how does it feel?

710
00:52:17,080 --> 00:52:18,638
Bloody marvelous.

711
00:52:18,720 --> 00:52:19,755
Really?

712
00:52:19,840 --> 00:52:21,398
Is the ventilator
a little fast?

713
00:52:22,320 --> 00:52:23,639
Well, maybe a little.

714
00:52:23,720 --> 00:52:25,438
Yeah? Is that better?

715
00:52:25,520 --> 00:52:27,272
Yeah, that's better.

716
00:52:28,040 --> 00:52:29,520
How long does
the battery last, Teddy?

717
00:52:29,560 --> 00:52:31,152
Up to three hours,
we think.

718
00:52:31,240 --> 00:52:32,536
Isn't this a case
where a little more

719
00:52:32,560 --> 00:52:33,760
certainty would
be appropriate?

720
00:52:33,840 --> 00:52:35,432
Well, there's a mains lead
as well.

721
00:52:35,520 --> 00:52:37,829
Teddy, you're a genius.

722
00:52:37,920 --> 00:52:39,816
Well, to be honest, it all
turned out to be pretty basic.

723
00:52:39,840 --> 00:52:42,308
I used a bicycle chain
and Sturmey-Archer gears.

724
00:52:42,400 --> 00:52:44,994
I don't know why
no one's done it before.

725
00:52:45,080 --> 00:52:49,312
I'll tell you why.
Because you're not a doctor.

726
00:52:49,400 --> 00:52:52,392
There's no one to tell you
it can't be done.

727
00:53:02,520 --> 00:53:03,953
(MATRON CLEARS THROAT)

728
00:53:04,080 --> 00:53:05,991
Oh, hello, Matron.
Hello, Matron.

729
00:53:06,120 --> 00:53:07,800
Oh, we've got an
appointment with Dr. Khan.

730
00:53:09,760 --> 00:53:12,228
DIANA: Dr. Khan.
ROBIN: Ah, hello, Dr. Khan.

731
00:53:12,520 --> 00:53:13,520
Huh?

732
00:53:13,600 --> 00:53:14,669
Paddy.
Oh.

733
00:53:14,760 --> 00:53:16,079
Robin.

734
00:53:16,160 --> 00:53:18,993
This really is
quite something.

735
00:53:19,080 --> 00:53:20,798
Jammy bastard.

736
00:53:21,840 --> 00:53:23,558
What in God's name
is that?

737
00:53:31,880 --> 00:53:35,589
Did you give permission for this
contraption to be brought into my ward?

738
00:53:35,680 --> 00:53:37,636
Well, actually, sir,
Mr. Cavend...

739
00:53:37,720 --> 00:53:39,472
It's hard enough
for our patients

740
00:53:39,560 --> 00:53:41,198
to accept the conditions
of their lives

741
00:53:41,320 --> 00:53:45,233
without raising false hopes that can
only leave them more dissatisfied.

742
00:53:45,320 --> 00:53:46,673
Now, where you come from,

743
00:53:46,760 --> 00:53:50,514
it may be common practice to
play games with people's lives.

744
00:53:50,600 --> 00:53:52,556
Here it is not.

745
00:53:52,640 --> 00:53:54,710
Is that understood?

746
00:53:54,800 --> 00:53:56,074
Good.

747
00:53:59,160 --> 00:54:01,720
It was lovely to see you,
Dr. Entwistle.

748
00:54:02,840 --> 00:54:06,549
Oh... That man's
a pompous idiot.

749
00:54:06,680 --> 00:54:08,079
You must want to
smack him.

750
00:54:08,160 --> 00:54:10,720
Believe me, I'm used to it.
Well...

751
00:54:10,800 --> 00:54:14,759
You'd think he'd want to get chairs
like this for all his patients.

752
00:54:14,840 --> 00:54:16,990
Well, Paddy, looks like
you owe me a fiver.

753
00:54:17,080 --> 00:54:19,355
Not so quick, pal.

754
00:54:19,440 --> 00:54:22,557
You could drop off
your perch tomorrow.

755
00:54:23,440 --> 00:54:24,759
Aww.

756
00:54:24,840 --> 00:54:26,432
Is it safe, Doctor?

757
00:54:26,520 --> 00:54:28,033
I don't know, Paddy.

758
00:54:28,160 --> 00:54:30,310
I've never seen
anything like this before.

759
00:54:30,400 --> 00:54:32,470
Goes five miles an hour

760
00:54:33,760 --> 00:54:35,990
with a strong wind
behind you.

761
00:54:36,080 --> 00:54:39,914
I'd advise waiting a little while longer.
Test its limits.

762
00:54:40,040 --> 00:54:43,874
Yes, quite right. Let me find
the breaking point for it.

763
00:54:43,960 --> 00:54:46,474
No, we're not going to test
Robin until he breaks.

764
00:54:46,560 --> 00:54:50,838
Well, actually, that's
exactly what we're doing.

765
00:54:50,920 --> 00:54:52,656
DIANA: You're doing better
than all his other patients.

766
00:54:52,680 --> 00:54:53,874
That's what he said.

767
00:54:53,960 --> 00:54:56,076
Poor old Paddy, though.

768
00:54:56,200 --> 00:54:58,714
I wish we could
somehow break him out, too.

769
00:55:02,040 --> 00:55:03,632
(GASPS)
(SCOFFS)

770
00:55:03,720 --> 00:55:05,597
It isn't kind to let
them out like that.

771
00:55:05,680 --> 00:55:07,671
On the street,
where everyone can see.

772
00:55:07,760 --> 00:55:11,514
Believe me, ladies, my distress
is far greater than yours.

773
00:56:21,640 --> 00:56:23,437
Bloggs told me
the other day

774
00:56:23,520 --> 00:56:26,671
that all our friends were convinced
that I'd give up on you.

775
00:56:28,600 --> 00:56:32,434
Apparently, they saw me as
some kind of pampered nitwit.

776
00:56:33,920 --> 00:56:36,559
Well, you were
a pampered nitwit.

777
00:56:36,640 --> 00:56:37,709
Oh, was I?

778
00:56:37,800 --> 00:56:40,314
Well, it didn't stop you
running after me, did it?

779
00:56:41,480 --> 00:56:43,914
Well, no, I've got
nothing against nitwits

780
00:56:44,000 --> 00:56:45,911
as long as they're pretty.

781
00:56:46,000 --> 00:56:48,355
Well, you're stuck
with me now.

782
00:56:48,480 --> 00:56:50,994
Yeah, I suppose I am.
Mmm.

783
00:56:53,000 --> 00:56:56,231
Just think, all those
affairs I could have had.

784
00:56:56,480 --> 00:56:57,480
Oh.

785
00:56:57,680 --> 00:56:59,159
And me.

786
00:56:59,240 --> 00:57:00,719
It's not too late
for you.

787
00:57:00,800 --> 00:57:02,518
Isn't it?

788
00:57:02,600 --> 00:57:05,990
What, and come back and find
you've popped off while I was out?

789
00:57:06,920 --> 00:57:08,672
(GROANING)

790
00:57:09,520 --> 00:57:11,750
That would rather spoil
the party, wouldn't it?

791
00:57:11,840 --> 00:57:13,193
Yes, it would.

792
00:57:15,920 --> 00:57:18,150
(SIGHS) Hold on.

793
00:57:22,200 --> 00:57:24,191
Look. I found Daddy.

794
00:57:25,520 --> 00:57:28,114
DIANA: That's Daddy
when he was a soldier.

795
00:57:28,200 --> 00:57:30,236
JONATHAN: Was he a soldier?

796
00:57:30,320 --> 00:57:31,514
DIANA: Yes, he was.

797
00:57:35,040 --> 00:57:39,670
And then (GASPS) this is us
when we were in Africa.

798
00:57:39,760 --> 00:57:42,399
That's where you were born.
(GASPS) And what are those?

799
00:57:42,520 --> 00:57:43,794
JONATHAN: Elephants.

800
00:57:43,880 --> 00:57:45,154
DIANA: They're elephants.

801
00:57:45,240 --> 00:57:47,629
JONATHAN: You saw elephants?

802
00:57:47,720 --> 00:57:49,153
DIANA: Yes, we did.

803
00:57:49,240 --> 00:57:50,958
You're so lucky.

804
00:57:51,040 --> 00:57:52,632
Yes, we were.

805
00:57:54,280 --> 00:57:57,431
JONATHAN: Can we go to
Africa one day, Daddy?

806
00:58:14,600 --> 00:58:16,716
I'm so sorry.

807
00:58:23,280 --> 00:58:25,271
Me, too.

808
00:58:31,720 --> 00:58:34,553
(KETTLE WHISTLING)

809
00:58:35,600 --> 00:58:38,592
Right, I'd better
sort out tea.

810
00:58:40,200 --> 00:58:43,033
Can we go to Africa,
please, Daddy?

811
00:58:46,400 --> 00:58:48,675
Wouldn't that be
an adventure?

812
00:58:48,760 --> 00:58:50,557
I could push you.

813
00:58:50,640 --> 00:58:53,279
Rather a long way
to push, J.

814
00:58:53,360 --> 00:58:55,271
I don't mind.

815
00:58:56,560 --> 00:58:59,074
ROBIN: Are you clever?
JONATHAN: Yes.

816
00:58:59,160 --> 00:59:01,151
ROBIN: Can you prove it?

817
00:59:01,480 --> 00:59:03,994
(KETTLE CONTINUES WHISTLING)

818
00:59:04,160 --> 00:59:05,832
(ROBIN AND JONATHAN LAUGHING)

819
00:59:05,920 --> 00:59:08,559
Okay, maybe you are.
Do you know what?

820
00:59:10,560 --> 00:59:12,391
(SNIFFLES)

821
00:59:19,480 --> 00:59:21,710
(GRUNTING)
Maybe you are strong enough.

822
00:59:22,760 --> 00:59:24,751
Mummy.
Yes?

823
00:59:25,800 --> 00:59:28,473
This chair-pushing business.

824
00:59:29,360 --> 00:59:30,793
Mmm?

825
00:59:30,960 --> 00:59:34,509
Is it quite hard to do
over long distances?

826
00:59:34,600 --> 00:59:37,114
Well, it's harder than a pram,
I can tell you.

827
00:59:37,480 --> 00:59:38,754
Oh...

828
00:59:38,840 --> 00:59:40,034
Jonathan?

829
00:59:40,880 --> 00:59:43,474
We're going to have to do some
thinking about this, aren't we?

830
00:59:43,640 --> 00:59:44,993
Mmm-hmm.

831
00:59:45,080 --> 00:59:47,310
(WHIRRING)

832
00:59:48,080 --> 00:59:50,275
(BELL TINKLING)

833
00:59:52,160 --> 00:59:54,276
MECHANIC: As per your design,
Mr. Cavendish.

834
00:59:54,400 --> 00:59:56,436
Be nice.

835
00:59:56,520 --> 00:59:58,511
MECHANIC:
Takes up to 300 pounds.

836
00:59:59,000 --> 01:00:00,718
(DOORS SLAM)

837
01:00:01,440 --> 01:00:02,873
My God.

838
01:00:04,960 --> 01:00:07,394
Hydraulic lifting mechanism.

839
01:00:07,480 --> 01:00:09,994
You won't see that
in a Bedford anywhere else.

840
01:00:11,280 --> 01:00:12,280
What do you think?

841
01:00:15,200 --> 01:00:16,792
What is it?

842
01:00:17,240 --> 01:00:19,231
It's a little dark
in the back.

843
01:00:19,960 --> 01:00:22,394
I feel rather like
luggage is the only thing.

844
01:00:23,800 --> 01:00:25,438
I just thought...

845
01:00:25,520 --> 01:00:28,114
Being as the wheelchair
has to be got in,

846
01:00:28,200 --> 01:00:30,270
the back seemed...

847
01:00:32,000 --> 01:00:34,150
Yes. Yes.

848
01:00:35,000 --> 01:00:36,319
Have you sat in the back?

849
01:00:36,400 --> 01:00:38,356
Me? Well, no.

850
01:00:38,440 --> 01:00:40,237
But, then I'm not, um...

851
01:00:40,320 --> 01:00:41,389
I'm not...

852
01:00:41,920 --> 01:00:42,955
Uh...

853
01:00:43,040 --> 01:00:44,553
You're not luggage, are you?

854
01:00:45,560 --> 01:00:46,595
(SIGHS IN FRUSTRATION)

855
01:00:46,680 --> 01:00:49,353
Please don't think I'm not grateful.
I truly am.

856
01:00:53,120 --> 01:00:54,553
You want to sit in the front?

857
01:00:56,200 --> 01:00:58,794
I don't think
that's possible, is it?

858
01:00:58,880 --> 01:01:03,351
I suppose if I took out
the front seat...

859
01:01:10,120 --> 01:01:12,680
(DIANA AND ROBIN SINGING)

860
01:01:15,640 --> 01:01:17,710
(LAUGHING)

861
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:33,877
(BOTH YELL)

862
01:01:52,400 --> 01:01:54,118
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

863
01:01:54,200 --> 01:01:55,792
BOY: Wait for me!
Wait for me!

864
01:01:55,880 --> 01:01:56,915
HARRY: Careful!

865
01:01:57,000 --> 01:01:58,991
Hi, there, little one.
Ought to be shot.

866
01:02:00,720 --> 01:02:02,711
Robin's amazing,
isn't he?

867
01:02:03,720 --> 01:02:04,755
It's not a bore.

868
01:02:04,840 --> 01:02:06,671
I feel I can
talk to you, Robin.

869
01:02:07,640 --> 01:02:09,710
Mum, Mum,
I'm going in to bat.

870
01:02:09,800 --> 01:02:12,030
Oh, are you? Brilliant.
You go get them.

871
01:02:12,160 --> 01:02:13,576
Good luck, Jonathan.
Go on. Thanks, Mum.

872
01:02:13,600 --> 01:02:15,795
Lucy walked out
a month ago now.

873
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:20,150
It's been a long time
coming, I suppose.

874
01:02:20,280 --> 01:02:21,280
ROBIN: Oh...

875
01:02:21,360 --> 01:02:25,751
Rory, I'm so sorry.
That's rather rough on you.

876
01:02:27,160 --> 01:02:29,628
Life's a shitty business,
isn't it?

877
01:02:29,720 --> 01:02:32,598
There you are, trying
to get on with life,

878
01:02:32,680 --> 01:02:35,148
and then,
out of nowhere, crack,

879
01:02:35,240 --> 01:02:37,231
everything comes
tumbling down.

880
01:02:39,240 --> 01:02:40,639
(SIGHS)

881
01:02:42,080 --> 01:02:43,832
Rory, grab my drink.
Let's have a toast.

882
01:02:44,840 --> 01:02:47,798
What are we drinking to?
Hmm?

883
01:02:50,360 --> 01:02:52,351
New dawns.

884
01:02:55,680 --> 01:02:57,636
New dawns.

885
01:02:57,720 --> 01:02:59,199
You've made a real
hash of that ham.

886
01:02:59,280 --> 01:03:03,034
Rubbish, Bloggs. You did that.
I've done this. Beautifully.

887
01:03:03,120 --> 01:03:05,953
Do you want it?
Yes. Thank you.

888
01:03:06,040 --> 01:03:08,031
Look at Robin now.
Look at him.

889
01:03:08,880 --> 01:03:10,096
HARRY: Unbelievable.
DAVID: How does he do that?

890
01:03:10,120 --> 01:03:12,953
Well, he proposed
to me yesterday.

891
01:03:13,040 --> 01:03:14,189
Of course he did.

892
01:03:14,280 --> 01:03:16,714
Yeah. And I'm so fond
of him.

893
01:03:16,800 --> 01:03:18,631
The only girl we've
got is you, Bloggs.

894
01:03:18,720 --> 01:03:20,472
Oh, do shut up.
(LAUGHING)

895
01:03:20,560 --> 01:03:22,073
But he's no beauty.

896
01:03:22,880 --> 01:03:24,080
RORY: It's not
just the pain...

897
01:03:24,120 --> 01:03:26,031
Is he actually ugly?

898
01:03:29,400 --> 01:03:31,630
Um... Well, yes.

899
01:03:31,720 --> 01:03:34,075
ROBIN: No, no, no,
that's wonderful.

900
01:03:34,880 --> 01:03:36,393
PAMELA: Why is that wonderful?

901
01:03:36,480 --> 01:03:38,994
Well, because good-looking
men are bone idle.

902
01:03:39,080 --> 01:03:41,275
Ugly men
will get things done.

903
01:03:43,480 --> 01:03:46,313
RORY: So pointless. How do you
get over something like that?

904
01:03:46,400 --> 01:03:47,958
Yep, you're right.

905
01:03:48,040 --> 01:03:53,194
RORY: Lost in the darkness
and silence, but it hurts...

906
01:03:53,280 --> 01:03:56,317
And I will get over it.
I know I will get over it,

907
01:03:56,400 --> 01:03:57,833
but it's just
going to take time,

908
01:03:57,920 --> 01:03:59,717
and at the moment,
I just need a bit of...

909
01:04:00,160 --> 01:04:02,151
(CHEERING)

910
01:04:03,680 --> 01:04:04,829
MAN: It's a six!

911
01:04:04,920 --> 01:04:06,399
Yes! Yes!

912
01:04:06,480 --> 01:04:08,914
Dad! Dad, did you see that?

913
01:04:10,200 --> 01:04:13,192
HARRY: Well done, Jonathan!
MAN: A six!

914
01:04:15,440 --> 01:04:16,555
So?

915
01:04:17,160 --> 01:04:18,912
Mmm?

916
01:04:20,600 --> 01:04:22,511
Did you enjoy that?

917
01:04:22,600 --> 01:04:23,749
Well...

918
01:04:25,360 --> 01:04:27,715
You were surrounded
by admirers.

919
01:04:28,840 --> 01:04:30,751
Yes, as were you.

920
01:04:31,560 --> 01:04:33,198
Me?
Yeah.

921
01:04:34,480 --> 01:04:36,835
Rory Stewart for one.

922
01:04:36,960 --> 01:04:38,359
Oh, Rory.

923
01:04:40,800 --> 01:04:43,314
Lucy's really
messed him about.

924
01:04:43,520 --> 01:04:45,431
Hmm?
Mmm.

925
01:04:46,280 --> 01:04:48,191
I feel so sorry
for him.

926
01:04:49,480 --> 01:04:55,237
He says he spends his evenings
alone watching television.

927
01:04:57,760 --> 01:05:01,992
I suppose he'd like you
to relieve his loneliness.

928
01:05:06,760 --> 01:05:08,034
Well, I'm not going to.

929
01:05:09,040 --> 01:05:11,349
You can
if you want to, darling.

930
01:05:12,760 --> 01:05:14,273
Oh.

931
01:05:16,480 --> 01:05:19,711
You're giving me
permission, are you?

932
01:05:28,240 --> 01:05:32,279
I do sometimes
worry that, um,

933
01:05:36,320 --> 01:05:38,550
you don't have enough fun.

934
01:05:38,640 --> 01:05:40,631
Don't worry about me.
No?

935
01:05:40,880 --> 01:05:42,359
Mmm-mmm.

936
01:05:42,680 --> 01:05:44,113
I'm all right.

937
01:05:44,960 --> 01:05:46,279
Are you sure?

938
01:05:46,360 --> 01:05:47,759
I think so.

939
01:05:52,280 --> 01:05:53,315
Mmm...

940
01:05:53,400 --> 01:05:55,391
We manage, don't we?

941
01:05:58,760 --> 01:06:00,751
That's easy for me.

942
01:06:03,640 --> 01:06:05,995
I just sit here while
you do all the work.

943
01:06:06,200 --> 01:06:07,633
(BOTH CHUCKLE)

944
01:06:08,080 --> 01:06:10,071
DIANA: Good old
selfish Robin.

945
01:06:12,000 --> 01:06:14,958
Oh, I say, Diana.
Run away with me.

946
01:06:18,440 --> 01:06:19,839
Where?

947
01:06:23,720 --> 01:06:25,995
ROBIN: Spain.
(LAUGHS)

948
01:06:26,080 --> 01:06:27,479
DIANA: Spain?

949
01:06:28,240 --> 01:06:30,470
We can't. Robin.

950
01:06:30,840 --> 01:06:31,840
(ROBIN WHINES)

951
01:06:32,320 --> 01:06:36,029
DIANA: Robin. Oh, you really
mean it, don't you?

952
01:06:36,120 --> 01:06:38,111
Now how on Earth
do we go to Spain?

953
01:06:38,200 --> 01:06:39,480
ROBIN: Well, by plane,
of course.

954
01:06:39,520 --> 01:06:42,956
DIANA: Darling, how do
we get you on a plane?

955
01:07:04,280 --> 01:07:05,679
(SCREAMING)

956
01:07:05,760 --> 01:07:06,829
(WHOOPING)

957
01:07:10,800 --> 01:07:12,119
Oh, my God!

958
01:07:20,280 --> 01:07:21,679
Whoa!
(BLOGGS SCREAMING)

959
01:07:21,760 --> 01:07:23,920
Are you all right, Jonathan?
Bloggs, are you all right?

960
01:07:26,040 --> 01:07:28,110
(ALL SCREAMING)

961
01:07:41,960 --> 01:07:44,235
(LAUGHING)

962
01:07:45,520 --> 01:07:47,590
(NEIGHS)

963
01:08:00,080 --> 01:08:01,399
BLOGGS: Come on, then,
you start.

964
01:08:01,480 --> 01:08:03,516
JONATHAN: I spy
with my little eye...

965
01:08:03,640 --> 01:08:04,920
DIANA: The house
is on the beach,

966
01:08:04,960 --> 01:08:06,598
and I brought
a long extension lead,

967
01:08:06,680 --> 01:08:08,671
so in theory you can stay
out all day if you like.

968
01:08:10,520 --> 01:08:12,829
Did you remember
to pack my parasol?

969
01:08:12,920 --> 01:08:15,832
Yes, darling, and I also
brought pints of sun cream.

970
01:08:15,920 --> 01:08:17,911
ROBIN: You're just an angel,
aren't you?

971
01:08:19,240 --> 01:08:22,676
Darling, we should charge
the chair battery.

972
01:08:22,800 --> 01:08:24,552
Oh, good idea. Uh...

973
01:08:24,640 --> 01:08:26,790
Bloggs.
BLOGGS: Yes?

974
01:08:26,880 --> 01:08:28,677
Can you see a cable
down there on the floor?

975
01:08:28,760 --> 01:08:30,056
Sorry. I can't take
my eyes off the road.

976
01:08:30,080 --> 01:08:31,911
Yes, I can. London.

977
01:08:32,000 --> 01:08:34,798
There's a plug board on the
side of the wheelchair.

978
01:08:34,920 --> 01:08:37,514
Can you plug that into the
second socket for me?

979
01:08:37,600 --> 01:08:39,636
BLOGGS: Uh, yes, I see it.
Second socket?

980
01:08:39,760 --> 01:08:40,760
DIANA: Second socket.

981
01:08:41,760 --> 01:08:42,795
BLOGGS: Yeah.

982
01:08:42,880 --> 01:08:43,949
(JONATHAN SCREAMS)

983
01:08:44,040 --> 01:08:45,951
Oh, God. Sorry.
Something's...

984
01:08:46,040 --> 01:08:47,336
I don't know.
DIANA: The ventilator.

985
01:08:47,360 --> 01:08:48,873
JONATHAN: It's burning! Mum!

986
01:08:48,960 --> 01:08:50,473
DIANA: What's happened
to the...

987
01:08:50,560 --> 01:08:53,074
Robin. Robin.
BLOGGS: I'm really sorry.

988
01:08:53,200 --> 01:08:55,111
Just pull over. Jonathan,
are you all right?

989
01:08:55,200 --> 01:08:57,839
JONATHAN: Yes, Mum.
DIANA: Get the hand pump.

990
01:08:57,920 --> 01:08:59,200
BLOGGS: We need to open
the door.

991
01:08:59,320 --> 01:09:01,231
DIANA: All right,
all right, all right.

992
01:09:01,320 --> 01:09:02,536
Bloggs, get Robin's door.
BLOGGS: Stop here.

993
01:09:02,560 --> 01:09:04,520
DIANA: I'm stopping.
I'm stopping. I'm stopping...

994
01:09:09,200 --> 01:09:10,394
(ALL COUGHING)

995
01:09:10,480 --> 01:09:11,708
DIANA: Robin.

996
01:09:11,800 --> 01:09:13,631
Bloggs, the bag.

997
01:09:15,720 --> 01:09:16,914
Jonathan, are you all right?

998
01:09:17,000 --> 01:09:18,035
JONATHAN: Yes, Mum.

999
01:09:18,120 --> 01:09:19,553
BLOGGS: Sorry, Robin.

1000
01:09:20,400 --> 01:09:22,776
Oh, God, I knew something like
this would happen. I just knew it.

1001
01:09:22,800 --> 01:09:23,800
What did I do?

1002
01:09:23,880 --> 01:09:24,915
I don't know.

1003
01:09:25,000 --> 01:09:26,353
The ventilator's broken.

1004
01:09:26,440 --> 01:09:28,237
Robin, are you all right?
I'm fine. I'm fine.

1005
01:09:28,560 --> 01:09:29,595
(COUGHING)

1006
01:09:31,120 --> 01:09:32,917
Jonathan. (COUGHING)

1007
01:09:38,760 --> 01:09:40,557
Do you know
how to fix it?

1008
01:09:45,000 --> 01:09:46,000
No.

1009
01:09:47,200 --> 01:09:48,428
No, I don't.

1010
01:09:50,360 --> 01:09:52,669
Sorry, Diana. I just
don't know what I did.

1011
01:09:53,760 --> 01:09:55,352
Neither do I.

1012
01:09:58,720 --> 01:10:01,280
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

1013
01:10:03,160 --> 01:10:06,038
Oh, God.
Do you speak English?

1014
01:10:07,120 --> 01:10:09,793
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

1015
01:10:09,880 --> 01:10:11,711
Just a little.
We need a mechanic.

1016
01:10:11,800 --> 01:10:15,031
No, no, we don't. No, no.
What we need is a telephone.

1017
01:10:15,120 --> 01:10:16,439
A telephone.

1018
01:10:16,640 --> 01:10:17,868
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

1019
01:10:17,960 --> 01:10:19,359
Yes.

1020
01:10:20,120 --> 01:10:22,156
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

1021
01:10:24,120 --> 01:10:25,473
Uh...

1022
01:10:25,720 --> 01:10:30,350
I take for you to Torredembarra
to find for telephone.

1023
01:10:30,480 --> 01:10:31,674
Yes. Yes.
Is okay?

1024
01:10:31,760 --> 01:10:34,228
Yes, yes, yes. Jonathan, could
you get my handbag, darling?

1025
01:10:34,320 --> 01:10:35,878
Thank you, yes.

1026
01:10:36,000 --> 01:10:37,069
(SPEAKS SPANISH)
Yes, yes.

1027
01:10:37,160 --> 01:10:40,436
Bloggs, Bloggs, Bloggs, Bloggs.
It's rather fast.

1028
01:10:40,560 --> 01:10:42,551
You don't have to go so fast.
Sorry.

1029
01:10:42,640 --> 01:10:46,030
Don't go so fast.
I'm not a balloon.

1030
01:10:47,160 --> 01:10:48,275
DIANA: Bloggs.
BLOGGS: Yeah.

1031
01:10:48,360 --> 01:10:51,272
Can you go with this man,
find a telephone and call Teddy Hall?

1032
01:10:51,360 --> 01:10:52,816
He'll either be at home
or at the workshop.

1033
01:10:52,840 --> 01:10:54,796
That's the Littlemore number.
In England?

1034
01:10:54,880 --> 01:10:57,155
Yes. Just tell him
what's happened,

1035
01:10:57,240 --> 01:10:58,912
and that we'll
wait for him here.

1036
01:10:59,000 --> 01:11:01,434
Yeah. We'll wait for him to
fly out from England?

1037
01:11:01,520 --> 01:11:03,431
Yes. Can you just go, please?
Yeah.

1038
01:11:03,520 --> 01:11:06,796
Bloggs, just while
you're out, grab us a...

1039
01:11:07,480 --> 01:11:10,711
Pick up some sausage
and a nice bit of bread.

1040
01:11:11,680 --> 01:11:13,238
And a bottle of red wine.

1041
01:11:13,720 --> 01:11:15,199
Corkscrew.

1042
01:11:16,200 --> 01:11:17,553
Good luck.

1043
01:11:22,400 --> 01:11:23,435
Hola.

1044
01:11:23,520 --> 01:11:24,919
I'm not saying it.

1045
01:11:25,120 --> 01:11:27,315
(BOTH SPEAKING SPANISH)

1046
01:11:27,920 --> 01:11:29,911
I hope you can hear me.
BLOGGS: Sorry!

1047
01:11:40,880 --> 01:11:42,154
DIANA: Mmm-hmm?

1048
01:11:50,400 --> 01:11:52,391
A rather pleasant
temperature.

1049
01:11:54,200 --> 01:11:58,079
Reminds me of Nairobi.

1050
01:12:00,240 --> 01:12:01,798
You all right there,
Jonathan?

1051
01:12:01,920 --> 01:12:05,276
Yes, I'm fine.
It's quite easy, really.

1052
01:12:05,640 --> 01:12:07,153
Oh?

1053
01:12:07,280 --> 01:12:08,920
You really are doing
brilliantly, darling.

1054
01:12:08,960 --> 01:12:10,029
Truly.
You really are.

1055
01:12:10,080 --> 01:12:12,196
I'll take over in a moment.
I'm okay.

1056
01:12:13,120 --> 01:12:14,189
Really.

1057
01:12:18,240 --> 01:12:22,153
Oh, God. I wonder what it
is they think we're doing.

1058
01:12:22,240 --> 01:12:25,471
Why, we've just gone
on holiday in a lay-by.

1059
01:12:25,560 --> 01:12:27,039
It's perfectly normal.

1060
01:12:27,120 --> 01:12:28,553
Cheers.
Cheers.

1061
01:12:28,640 --> 01:12:30,073
Cheers, darling.

1062
01:12:31,040 --> 01:12:32,758
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

1063
01:12:45,960 --> 01:12:48,269
He say God makes a joke.

1064
01:13:00,000 --> 01:13:01,592
So we have party.

1065
01:13:01,840 --> 01:13:03,159
Sí. Sí.

1066
01:13:03,240 --> 01:13:04,639
(LAUGHING)

1067
01:13:04,760 --> 01:13:07,797
Yeah... Well, that's quite
all right, isn't it?

1068
01:13:08,080 --> 01:13:09,718
(ALL TOAST IN SPANISH)

1069
01:13:10,480 --> 01:13:13,438
(MUSIC PLAYING)
(PEOPLE LAUGHING)

1070
01:13:17,160 --> 01:13:19,310
(PLAYING SOFT LATIN MUSIC)

1071
01:13:49,000 --> 01:13:50,991
Do you know
who'd love this?

1072
01:13:56,200 --> 01:13:57,633
Paddy.

1073
01:14:06,080 --> 01:14:08,719
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)
(RHYTHMIC CLAPPING)

1074
01:14:28,440 --> 01:14:30,032
TEDDY: For heaven's sake.
DIANA: Teddy!

1075
01:14:30,120 --> 01:14:31,678
BLOGGS: Teddy!
Hello, darling.

1076
01:14:31,760 --> 01:14:33,512
Oh, God.

1077
01:14:33,600 --> 01:14:36,797
You could at least have the decency
to be on the point of death.

1078
01:14:36,880 --> 01:14:38,074
What...

1079
01:14:40,040 --> 01:14:41,758
What the hell is this?

1080
01:14:43,680 --> 01:14:47,070
There. Now,
let's fire her up.

1081
01:14:47,760 --> 01:14:50,228
(RESPIRATOR STARTING)
(ALL CHEERING)

1082
01:14:50,560 --> 01:14:53,120
I'm glad someone's happy.
(CHUCKLES)

1083
01:14:53,360 --> 01:14:56,830
God knows how you managed to
make such a balls-up of this.

1084
01:14:56,920 --> 01:14:58,876
My fault, I'm afraid.

1085
01:14:58,960 --> 01:15:02,555
What are you all doing gallivanting
in Spain in the first place?

1086
01:15:02,640 --> 01:15:04,039
It's my fault,
I'm afraid.

1087
01:15:04,120 --> 01:15:08,159
Well, this isn't built for
trans-continental voyages.

1088
01:15:08,240 --> 01:15:10,196
I know, Ted. I'm sorry.

1089
01:15:10,280 --> 01:15:12,714
I wanted to see the sun
rise over the Med.

1090
01:15:12,800 --> 01:15:15,473
It rises over Drayton
St. Leonard's, too, you know.

1091
01:15:15,600 --> 01:15:17,875
(ALL LAUGHING)

1092
01:15:19,520 --> 01:15:23,559
(MUSIC PLAYING)
(ALL CHEERING)

1093
01:15:28,440 --> 01:15:29,714
ROBIN: Teddy?

1094
01:15:29,800 --> 01:15:32,189
Absolutely rather good
you're here.

1095
01:15:32,280 --> 01:15:35,033
I'm planning
an even greater escape.

1096
01:15:35,120 --> 01:15:37,176
TEDDY: Well, I'm not rescuing
you from anywhere else.

1097
01:15:37,200 --> 01:15:39,475
ROBIN: Oh, it's not
just me this time.

1098
01:15:39,560 --> 01:15:41,949
There's a good few more
that need rescuing.

1099
01:15:42,040 --> 01:15:43,040
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

1100
01:15:43,120 --> 01:15:45,270
Let's get this show
on the road!

1101
01:15:45,360 --> 01:15:47,032
Is that chair breathing?

1102
01:15:47,120 --> 01:15:49,315
Like a sleeping lion.
Glorious.

1103
01:15:49,440 --> 01:15:52,352
Is that Dr. Clement Aitken?
The same.

1104
01:15:52,440 --> 01:15:54,590
Very good, very good.
Teddy! Mind.

1105
01:15:54,680 --> 01:15:56,671
Hello.
This is Teddy Hall.

1106
01:15:57,840 --> 01:15:59,353
TEDDY: Oh, dear, dear, dear.

1107
01:15:59,440 --> 01:16:02,120
DR. AITKEN: I have never, in all my career,
seen anything like this.

1108
01:16:02,160 --> 01:16:04,720
You just made this up?
Well, pretty much, yes.

1109
01:16:04,800 --> 01:16:07,075
DR. AITKEN: Only way to get
anything done.

1110
01:16:07,160 --> 01:16:08,673
I like this man.
Is he a doctor?

1111
01:16:08,760 --> 01:16:12,548
Yes, and he's the Director of the
Disability Research Foundation.

1112
01:16:12,640 --> 01:16:13,640
Which he invented.

1113
01:16:13,680 --> 01:16:14,816
Yes, and made
himself director.

1114
01:16:14,840 --> 01:16:16,976
Well, if nobody else will do it,
you have to do it yourself.

1115
01:16:17,000 --> 01:16:19,389
Hello. What's this?

1116
01:16:19,480 --> 01:16:22,119
Oh, I'm having a go
at a Mark II version.

1117
01:16:22,200 --> 01:16:25,715
The trouble with the Mark I is
the battery is pretty poor,

1118
01:16:25,800 --> 01:16:27,438
and the pump's very noisy,

1119
01:16:27,560 --> 01:16:29,278
so I'm having a go
at using a solenoid.

1120
01:16:29,360 --> 01:16:31,157
Fascinating. So what is
the battery life?

1121
01:16:31,240 --> 01:16:33,390
On the Mark II,
about six hours.

1122
01:16:34,840 --> 01:16:37,035
How long have you been living
with this condition?

1123
01:16:38,520 --> 01:16:40,670
Eleven years so far.
Incredible.

1124
01:16:42,000 --> 01:16:43,718
Well, if these chairs
of yours really work,

1125
01:16:43,800 --> 01:16:45,119
I'm gonna need
a lot of them.

1126
01:16:45,200 --> 01:16:47,509
How many?
Hundreds.

1127
01:16:47,600 --> 01:16:50,558
Oh, well, I've been financing
the work myself up to now.

1128
01:16:50,640 --> 01:16:51,840
It hasn't set me back
too much,

1129
01:16:51,960 --> 01:16:56,272
but if we're to go into production,
we'll need proper funding.

1130
01:16:58,160 --> 01:17:00,799
The Department has
to take into consideration

1131
01:17:00,880 --> 01:17:02,836
the question of
cost-effectiveness.

1132
01:17:03,320 --> 01:17:06,869
The life expectancy
of polio patients

1133
01:17:07,000 --> 01:17:09,355
is less than average,
shall we say.

1134
01:17:10,560 --> 01:17:13,279
I'm sorry. I can't see how
I can, in all fairness,

1135
01:17:13,360 --> 01:17:15,112
make a case for funding.

1136
01:17:16,720 --> 01:17:18,199
I have to follow
the rules.

1137
01:17:18,320 --> 01:17:20,197
(ROBIN GROANING)

1138
01:17:24,040 --> 01:17:26,713
Rules are so paralyzing,
aren't they?

1139
01:17:27,480 --> 01:17:28,754
(DIANA CLEARS THROAT)

1140
01:17:29,360 --> 01:17:31,669
Of course, I do sympathize
with your condition.

1141
01:17:31,760 --> 01:17:33,352
Oh, yes. Likewise.

1142
01:17:43,960 --> 01:17:45,075
DIANA: Name?

1143
01:17:45,160 --> 01:17:46,798
ROBIN: Lady Jane Neville.

1144
01:17:47,600 --> 01:17:49,113
And good for?

1145
01:17:49,320 --> 01:17:50,719
Uh...

1146
01:17:51,400 --> 01:17:54,949
A thousand at least,
if she's in the mood.

1147
01:17:55,440 --> 01:17:57,829
Right. So are we
"plucky" or "pitiful"?

1148
01:17:57,920 --> 01:17:59,512
I think
definitely "plucky."

1149
01:17:59,600 --> 01:18:03,798
These old dowagers
are tough as nails.

1150
01:18:05,440 --> 01:18:07,431
Why does he make
that funny noise?

1151
01:18:09,760 --> 01:18:11,830
Well, that's
the wheelchair.

1152
01:18:11,920 --> 01:18:13,592
It does his breathing
for him.

1153
01:18:14,560 --> 01:18:16,835
Are you quite sure it's
safe for you to be out?

1154
01:18:18,920 --> 01:18:20,911
Seems to have worked
so far.

1155
01:18:21,640 --> 01:18:25,315
And what exactly is it
you want from me?

1156
01:18:27,120 --> 01:18:29,190
Well, we want more
of these chairs.

1157
01:18:29,280 --> 01:18:31,350
Yes, for people
like Robin.

1158
01:18:31,440 --> 01:18:33,351
At £200 a chair.

1159
01:18:33,440 --> 01:18:35,056
DIANA: Yes, which really
is excellent value.

1160
01:18:35,080 --> 01:18:36,149
Isn't it?
ROBIN: Well...

1161
01:18:36,240 --> 01:18:38,879
It would be five
for £1,000.

1162
01:18:38,960 --> 01:18:40,871
£1,000?

1163
01:18:40,960 --> 01:18:43,076
Well, 10 for £2,000.

1164
01:18:43,160 --> 01:18:45,515
£2,000?

1165
01:18:45,600 --> 01:18:48,831
You see, we knew
we could count on you.

1166
01:18:48,920 --> 01:18:50,273
Because you're
so generous.

1167
01:18:50,360 --> 01:18:51,634
Yes.

1168
01:18:53,280 --> 01:18:57,592
I don't usually find it difficult
to say no to spongers.

1169
01:18:58,200 --> 01:19:00,555
But with you there,

1170
01:19:00,640 --> 01:19:03,200
wheezing away in front of me,

1171
01:19:03,280 --> 01:19:06,511
(SIGHS) I suppose
I shall have to pay up.

1172
01:19:08,160 --> 01:19:10,435
So very kind of you.
So very kind.

1173
01:19:10,520 --> 01:19:11,669
So kind.

1174
01:19:18,760 --> 01:19:20,751
This is bloody marvelous.

1175
01:19:20,840 --> 01:19:22,159
ROBIN: Aww.

1176
01:19:22,400 --> 01:19:24,072
Do you feel safe?

1177
01:19:24,160 --> 01:19:26,515
I feel bloody terrified.
Ah...

1178
01:19:40,520 --> 01:19:42,875
(APPLAUSE AND CHEERING)

1179
01:19:44,600 --> 01:19:46,795
(CAMERAS CLICKING)

1180
01:19:48,200 --> 01:19:49,872
Hello, everyone.

1181
01:19:59,240 --> 01:20:01,310
My name is
Dr. Clement Aitken.

1182
01:20:01,440 --> 01:20:04,318
I'm the Director of the
Disability Research Foundation.

1183
01:20:04,400 --> 01:20:05,958
In this country,

1184
01:20:06,040 --> 01:20:09,476
there are hundreds of
severely disabled patients

1185
01:20:09,560 --> 01:20:13,519
currently living their entire
lives in hospital beds.

1186
01:20:13,600 --> 01:20:15,670
Worldwide,
there are thousands.

1187
01:20:15,760 --> 01:20:17,512
Do you think they like that?

1188
01:20:18,200 --> 01:20:21,033
If you want to get out,
give me a shout!

1189
01:20:21,360 --> 01:20:24,318
(PATIENTS SHOUTING)

1190
01:20:25,360 --> 01:20:26,873
ROBIN: How many
thousands worldwide?

1191
01:20:26,960 --> 01:20:28,552
Oh, tens of thousands,
maybe more.

1192
01:20:29,280 --> 01:20:32,158
No one's ever believed it's
possible to live as you do.

1193
01:20:32,240 --> 01:20:33,832
Well, we should show them.

1194
01:20:33,920 --> 01:20:35,956
What do you want now,
Robin, a world tour?

1195
01:20:36,040 --> 01:20:39,476
Well, there is a European
conference coming up in Germany

1196
01:20:39,560 --> 01:20:41,516
for severely disabled living.

1197
01:20:41,600 --> 01:20:43,989
All the so-called
key experts will be there.

1198
01:20:45,440 --> 01:20:47,954
Oh my giddy aunt!
If only they could see you...

1199
01:21:03,240 --> 01:21:06,198
I think he should be
in hospital. No?

1200
01:21:06,280 --> 01:21:08,271
You're quite right. No.

1201
01:21:09,160 --> 01:21:10,536
COLIN: You did check
we'd be able to fit

1202
01:21:10,560 --> 01:21:11,936
the wheelchair in,
didn't you, Bloggs?

1203
01:21:11,960 --> 01:21:14,554
Yes, of course, I did.
What do you take me for?

1204
01:21:14,680 --> 01:21:16,591
Thank God for that.
I know.

1205
01:21:16,680 --> 01:21:19,240
I never thought we'd actually make it...
Oh, sorry.

1206
01:21:19,320 --> 01:21:20,616
Oh, sorry.
No, it was probably my fault.

1207
01:21:20,640 --> 01:21:22,016
Pull out, pull out.
Let's pull out, that's it.

1208
01:21:22,040 --> 01:21:23,240
Straight,
straight, straight...

1209
01:21:23,320 --> 01:21:27,108
Straighten it up. In you go.
ALL: Oh!

1210
01:21:27,200 --> 01:21:29,416
DR. AITKEN: You're not gonna do it.
That's not gonna go through.

1211
01:21:29,440 --> 01:21:31,715
DIANA: Right.
Whose fault's this, then?

1212
01:21:31,800 --> 01:21:33,256
ROBIN: I think we're
going to struggle here.

1213
01:21:33,280 --> 01:21:35,919
Sorry, I didn't know I was
supposed to measure the doors.

1214
01:21:36,960 --> 01:21:38,136
It's the wheels
that are the problem.

1215
01:21:38,160 --> 01:21:39,456
COLIN: Yes, yes, yes, yes.
Good idea.

1216
01:21:39,480 --> 01:21:40,629
HARRY: Drag him back.

1217
01:21:40,720 --> 01:21:42,711
Listen, listen, listen.
DIANA: What?

1218
01:21:42,800 --> 01:21:45,109
We're gonna have to take
the inner door frame off.

1219
01:21:45,600 --> 01:21:46,600
Oh, well done, Clem.

1220
01:21:46,640 --> 01:21:47,840
Clem's done it,
Clem's done it.

1221
01:21:47,960 --> 01:21:49,632
(WOOD CRACKS)
(ALL GASP)

1222
01:21:50,960 --> 01:21:51,960
Clem's bloody done it.

1223
01:21:52,040 --> 01:21:53,360
HARRY: Clem,
that is looking good.

1224
01:21:55,880 --> 01:21:57,108
(PEOPLE SHUSHING)

1225
01:21:57,200 --> 01:21:58,519
Quick. Go, go.

1226
01:21:58,640 --> 01:22:00,296
DR. AITKEN: Get him in,
get him in, get him in.

1227
01:22:00,320 --> 01:22:01,514
Sorry.

1228
01:22:01,880 --> 01:22:03,029
HARRY: Go on.

1229
01:22:03,160 --> 01:22:05,151
(DIANA SHUSHING)
BLOGGS: Brilliant.

1230
01:22:16,600 --> 01:22:18,989
(DR. AITKEN SPEAKING GERMAN)

1231
01:22:27,200 --> 01:22:28,880
(IN ENGLISH) I want you
to see this, Robin.

1232
01:22:30,720 --> 01:22:31,789
Let me go in first.

1233
01:22:31,880 --> 01:22:33,916
You may give them
something of a shock.

1234
01:22:38,680 --> 01:22:40,272
Dr. Aitken?
Yes.

1235
01:22:40,360 --> 01:22:41,634
It's an honor.

1236
01:22:41,720 --> 01:22:43,517
Erik Langdorf.
I'm the Director.

1237
01:22:43,640 --> 01:22:45,710
Aha! My associates.

1238
01:22:47,520 --> 01:22:50,478
I have heard so much about your
care for the severely disabled.

1239
01:22:50,560 --> 01:22:51,675
This hospital is famous.

1240
01:22:53,160 --> 01:22:54,354
Please.

1241
01:23:20,120 --> 01:23:23,430
Such excellent
modern machinery.

1242
01:23:24,960 --> 01:23:26,791
And everything so clean.

1243
01:24:06,000 --> 01:24:07,991
The chair has a respirator?

1244
01:24:08,080 --> 01:24:09,798
Mmm-hmm.

1245
01:24:10,480 --> 01:24:13,119
(BOTH SPEAKING GERMAN)

1246
01:24:21,480 --> 01:24:23,675
(IN ENGLISH) Sorry,
but he must leave.

1247
01:24:23,760 --> 01:24:25,751
Of course.
How stupid of me.

1248
01:24:25,840 --> 01:24:27,068
Please understand.

1249
01:24:27,160 --> 01:24:30,232
We are Department of the
Bundesministerium des Innern.

1250
01:24:30,320 --> 01:24:31,673
If anything were to happen...

1251
01:24:31,760 --> 01:24:33,034
The Ministry of
the Interior?

1252
01:24:33,120 --> 01:24:34,997
Yes.
Like our Home Office?

1253
01:24:35,640 --> 01:24:37,119
Yes.

1254
01:24:37,200 --> 01:24:40,112
Don't they run
the prisons, too?

1255
01:24:40,640 --> 01:24:42,471
I believe so, yes.

1256
01:24:44,000 --> 01:24:46,309
Thank you so much,
Dr. Langdorf,

1257
01:24:46,400 --> 01:24:48,197
for giving us so much
of your time.

1258
01:25:04,480 --> 01:25:08,553
May I begin by noting
an interesting fact.

1259
01:25:10,520 --> 01:25:11,794
At this conference

1260
01:25:11,880 --> 01:25:16,158
on Managing The Lives
Of The Severely Disabled,

1261
01:25:17,880 --> 01:25:20,519
there are no
disabled people present.

1262
01:25:20,840 --> 01:25:22,717
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

1263
01:25:23,200 --> 01:25:26,590
Dr. Aitken, forgive me,

1264
01:25:26,680 --> 01:25:31,674
but the severely disabled
are on life-support machines.

1265
01:25:31,760 --> 01:25:33,796
So how could
they be present?

1266
01:25:33,920 --> 01:25:35,717
(LAUGHING CONTINUES)

1267
01:25:37,040 --> 01:25:41,989
Well, allow me to introduce
Mr. Robin Cavendish.

1268
01:25:52,040 --> 01:25:53,314
All right...

1269
01:25:55,840 --> 01:25:58,121
If I put that there, is it going to work?
Yeah, well done.

1270
01:26:02,360 --> 01:26:05,875
Robin, you have a question
to ask our hosts.

1271
01:26:05,960 --> 01:26:07,393
ROBIN: Yes, I do.

1272
01:26:09,760 --> 01:26:12,911
Why do you keep your
disabled people in prisons?

1273
01:26:13,720 --> 01:26:15,233
In prisons?

1274
01:26:15,880 --> 01:26:17,916
No. No.

1275
01:26:18,480 --> 01:26:20,357
We have some of
the finest facilities

1276
01:26:20,440 --> 01:26:21,998
in the world for
the severely disabled.

1277
01:26:22,080 --> 01:26:24,674
I know, but they're
run by prison guards.

1278
01:26:24,760 --> 01:26:26,193
No, not at all.

1279
01:26:26,280 --> 01:26:29,636
Well, patients are kept
out of sight.

1280
01:26:31,800 --> 01:26:36,032
Not treated as part
of healthy society.

1281
01:26:36,120 --> 01:26:37,872
I must ask
that you withdraw that.

1282
01:26:37,960 --> 01:26:41,157
Mr. Cavendish doesn't mean
to cause offense.

1283
01:26:41,240 --> 01:26:44,516
He's merely suggesting
that the severely disabled

1284
01:26:44,600 --> 01:26:47,194
can be better integrated
into society.

1285
01:26:47,280 --> 01:26:50,989
Absolutely. I can see
that you all care

1286
01:26:51,640 --> 01:26:55,758
very deeply about your disabled people.
I see that.

1287
01:26:57,840 --> 01:27:00,274
But let me ask you,
when you look at me,

1288
01:27:03,440 --> 01:27:05,351
what is it that you see?

1289
01:27:08,640 --> 01:27:10,153
Do you see a creature

1290
01:27:11,800 --> 01:27:13,836
that's barely alive?

1291
01:27:18,800 --> 01:27:22,679
Or do you see a man
that's escaped the confines

1292
01:27:24,320 --> 01:27:26,629
of the hospital walls?

1293
01:27:30,000 --> 01:27:32,468
Now, I have a machine

1294
01:27:34,320 --> 01:27:37,710
under this very seat
that breathes for me.

1295
01:27:42,840 --> 01:27:46,037
And at home, I have a
ventilator right by my bed.

1296
01:27:50,680 --> 01:27:53,319
I also have a remarkable
group of friends.

1297
01:27:55,880 --> 01:27:58,633
And, most vitally,
I have my wife.

1298
01:28:00,040 --> 01:28:03,157
But, as you see,
I can do nothing for myself.

1299
01:28:06,880 --> 01:28:08,871
And yet here I am.

1300
01:28:11,320 --> 01:28:13,880
Now, when I first became
paralyzed, I wanted to die.

1301
01:28:15,240 --> 01:28:17,231
Yeah, I wanted to die.
I did.

1302
01:28:19,320 --> 01:28:21,311
But my wife wouldn't let me.

1303
01:28:24,000 --> 01:28:26,195
She told me I had to live.

1304
01:28:27,880 --> 01:28:30,269
To see our son grow up.

1305
01:28:33,840 --> 01:28:35,558
So I went on living

1306
01:28:37,240 --> 01:28:39,071
because she told me to.

1307
01:28:40,440 --> 01:28:42,556
Because of her, really,

1308
01:28:44,080 --> 01:28:48,073
and with her and for her.

1309
01:28:51,040 --> 01:28:53,429
And every day since then,

1310
01:28:55,080 --> 01:28:57,594
I've accepted
the risk of dying

1311
01:28:59,760 --> 01:29:02,479
because I don't want
to just survive.

1312
01:29:06,760 --> 01:29:08,955
I want to truly live.

1313
01:29:14,160 --> 01:29:16,276
So I implore you,

1314
01:29:17,920 --> 01:29:20,115
go back to your hospitals,

1315
01:29:20,760 --> 01:29:23,433
and you tell
your disabled patients

1316
01:29:25,000 --> 01:29:27,833
that they too
can truly live.

1317
01:29:29,960 --> 01:29:31,951
You all have this power

1318
01:29:35,280 --> 01:29:40,513
to open the gates
and set them free.

1319
01:29:53,960 --> 01:29:56,235
(CHEERING)

1320
01:30:16,000 --> 01:30:17,718
DIANA: Jonathan!

1321
01:30:19,320 --> 01:30:20,548
Jonathan!

1322
01:30:25,280 --> 01:30:27,271
Help me turn him
on his side.

1323
01:30:30,160 --> 01:30:32,720
Jonathan. Help me turn him
on his side.

1324
01:30:35,320 --> 01:30:37,276
(GRUNTING)

1325
01:30:39,200 --> 01:30:40,235
That's it.

1326
01:30:40,320 --> 01:30:42,788
All right, love.
All right, darling.

1327
01:30:50,680 --> 01:30:52,272
It's all right.

1328
01:30:52,360 --> 01:30:55,511
All right, we can put him
on his back now. That's it.

1329
01:30:58,880 --> 01:31:00,359
All right, darling.

1330
01:31:01,720 --> 01:31:03,039
Robin?

1331
01:31:05,320 --> 01:31:07,356
Do what you can to clean
up the mess, darling.

1332
01:31:21,520 --> 01:31:26,230
ROBIN: It's all right.
It's all right.

1333
01:31:31,440 --> 01:31:34,398
It's all right, dear boy.
It's all right.

1334
01:31:37,560 --> 01:31:39,118
I'm afraid this is
what happens

1335
01:31:39,200 --> 01:31:41,634
after a number of years
on a respirator.

1336
01:31:41,720 --> 01:31:44,473
The lining of the lungs
becomes irritated.

1337
01:31:44,600 --> 01:31:47,637
You get small abrasions.
You get bleeding.

1338
01:31:48,640 --> 01:31:52,030
The fact is,
it's gonna get worse.

1339
01:31:52,120 --> 01:31:54,395
More bleeds.
Bigger bleeds.

1340
01:31:54,480 --> 01:32:00,316
And... Well, the risk is
you drown in your own blood.

1341
01:32:02,200 --> 01:32:04,794
(PEELING APPLES)

1342
01:32:52,000 --> 01:32:56,152
ROBIN: Remember that story
in Kenya about

1343
01:32:59,160 --> 01:33:01,390
Mau Mau prisoners?

1344
01:33:04,520 --> 01:33:05,919
Yes.
Ah...

1345
01:33:09,960 --> 01:33:11,951
Their leader said,

1346
01:33:15,640 --> 01:33:18,438
"I give my men
permission to die."

1347
01:33:22,800 --> 01:33:24,791
And then by morning,

1348
01:33:29,520 --> 01:33:31,636
they just all passed away.

1349
01:33:35,400 --> 01:33:38,676
And I have decided
it's time for me, too.

1350
01:33:41,640 --> 01:33:43,870
I'm going to let myself go.

1351
01:33:52,240 --> 01:33:54,037
And what about me?

1352
01:33:57,240 --> 01:33:59,879
You're going to be free
at last.

1353
01:34:00,720 --> 01:34:02,233
I don't want...

1354
01:34:02,320 --> 01:34:03,389
No.

1355
01:34:04,440 --> 01:34:05,555
No.

1356
01:34:06,240 --> 01:34:09,391
God, you're a stupid,
stupid man.

1357
01:34:11,560 --> 01:34:15,394
What do you think I've been
doing all these years?

1358
01:34:16,080 --> 01:34:17,399
Hmm?

1359
01:34:18,920 --> 01:34:21,354
Your life is my life.

1360
01:34:23,800 --> 01:34:24,949
And...

1361
01:34:25,040 --> 01:34:26,359
I'm sorry, Jonathan.

1362
01:34:26,440 --> 01:34:27,919
ROBIN: Jonathan.

1363
01:34:32,360 --> 01:34:34,351
You should let her be.

1364
01:34:42,720 --> 01:34:45,280
(DIANA YELLS)

1365
01:35:05,200 --> 01:35:07,668
All right. Fine.

1366
01:35:07,760 --> 01:35:09,876
Fine, have it your way.
You always do.

1367
01:35:11,040 --> 01:35:15,033
But don't you ever, ever say
that you did it for me.

1368
01:35:23,200 --> 01:35:25,236
You do know
that it's against the law.

1369
01:35:28,400 --> 01:35:31,233
Well, yes, but who's
going to know?

1370
01:35:33,400 --> 01:35:38,997
Well, if Diana or Jonathan
were to get involved,

1371
01:35:40,200 --> 01:35:42,156
could end up in prison.

1372
01:35:45,800 --> 01:35:47,916
They're not
going to be involved.

1373
01:35:48,760 --> 01:35:50,079
And what about you?

1374
01:35:50,160 --> 01:35:51,434
(SCOFFS) Me.

1375
01:35:54,360 --> 01:35:58,592
I've been breaking the rules
my whole life. (CHUCKLES)

1376
01:36:00,000 --> 01:36:02,150
(BOTH LAUGH)

1377
01:36:06,800 --> 01:36:08,279
(SIGHS)

1378
01:36:09,600 --> 01:36:11,670
So promise me you know
what you're asking.

1379
01:36:13,600 --> 01:36:15,795
Oh, yes, I know
what I'm asking.

1380
01:36:19,840 --> 01:36:21,478
We must buck him up.

1381
01:36:22,680 --> 01:36:27,117
You know, get him out
of this morbid frame of mind.

1382
01:36:27,680 --> 01:36:29,432
(SPOONS CLATTERING)
(WATER RUNNING)

1383
01:36:29,520 --> 01:36:32,159
Make him see how much
his friends need him.

1384
01:36:32,240 --> 01:36:36,950
Colin. We're not going to keep Robin
alive for the sake of his friends.

1385
01:36:40,320 --> 01:36:42,038
(SIGHS)

1386
01:36:44,960 --> 01:36:46,518
No, of course not.

1387
01:36:52,080 --> 01:36:54,036
But I expect they'd
like to say goodbye.

1388
01:36:54,320 --> 01:36:55,673
Oh...

1389
01:36:56,800 --> 01:36:58,153
Hi.

1390
01:36:58,240 --> 01:36:59,240
Toby.

1391
01:37:00,240 --> 01:37:02,629
He's telling everyone
it's his leaving party.

1392
01:37:02,720 --> 01:37:04,711
What, even the girls?
Trevor.

1393
01:37:04,960 --> 01:37:06,712
(TRIUMPHANT MUSIC PLAYING)
(APPLAUSE)

1394
01:37:06,880 --> 01:37:08,871
JONATHAN: Watch the steps.
Drop coming up.

1395
01:37:24,600 --> 01:37:26,955
(ALL CHEERING)

1396
01:37:39,520 --> 01:37:42,398
You're planning
another great escape.

1397
01:37:43,960 --> 01:37:46,235
Uh... It's time to go.

1398
01:37:49,080 --> 01:37:51,071
For me, anyway.

1399
01:37:53,800 --> 01:37:56,234
PADDY: Just like
the last time.

1400
01:37:57,240 --> 01:37:59,231
Not waiting for your friends.

1401
01:38:00,400 --> 01:38:03,153
No, you're too slow
for me, Paddy.

1402
01:38:05,440 --> 01:38:06,873
(SIGHS)

1403
01:38:07,440 --> 01:38:08,668
You owe me £5.

1404
01:38:09,040 --> 01:38:10,189
Ah...

1405
01:38:10,520 --> 01:38:11,520
(CHUCKLES)

1406
01:38:26,840 --> 01:38:28,432
(GLASS CLINKS)

1407
01:38:28,920 --> 01:38:32,151
Well, this is
a Saint-Émilion '59.

1408
01:38:32,240 --> 01:38:36,074
My last bottle of one of the
greatest wines ever made.

1409
01:38:36,160 --> 01:38:37,388
Jonathan, glasses, hmm?

1410
01:38:40,000 --> 01:38:41,558
Teddy.

1411
01:38:42,400 --> 01:38:45,153
Robin.
Harry.

1412
01:38:45,240 --> 01:38:48,835
We've been friends
for many, many years.

1413
01:38:49,760 --> 01:38:51,352
I'd just like to say...

1414
01:38:51,680 --> 01:38:53,432
(GRUNTING)
(ALL EXCLAIMING)

1415
01:38:53,520 --> 01:38:54,873
Harry.
Harry.

1416
01:38:54,960 --> 01:38:56,916
I broke a chair.
No, you didn't. You didn't.

1417
01:38:57,000 --> 01:38:59,150
You didn't.

1418
01:38:59,240 --> 01:39:00,639
Give him a drop of that.

1419
01:39:00,720 --> 01:39:01,840
COLIN: This'll sort you out.

1420
01:39:01,880 --> 01:39:03,016
This'll put hairs
on your chest.

1421
01:39:03,040 --> 01:39:06,271
Robin, old man,
here's to you.

1422
01:39:06,360 --> 01:39:08,635
I'm drinking to each
and every one of you.

1423
01:39:09,280 --> 01:39:11,191
MAN: Cheers, Robin.
HARRY: Cheers, old boy.

1424
01:39:12,520 --> 01:39:14,272
BLOGGS AND DAVID: (SINGING)
Goodbye-ee

1425
01:39:14,360 --> 01:39:15,713
Goodbye-ee

1426
01:39:15,800 --> 01:39:19,952
Wipe the tear,
baby dear, from your eye-ee

1427
01:39:20,040 --> 01:39:23,157
Though it's hard to part,
I know

1428
01:39:24,160 --> 01:39:27,277
I'll be tickled to death
to go

1429
01:39:27,360 --> 01:39:29,635
Don't cry-ee

1430
01:39:29,720 --> 01:39:31,517
(SINGING ALONG) Don't sigh-ee

1431
01:39:31,600 --> 01:39:35,354
There's a silver lining
in the sky-ee

1432
01:39:35,440 --> 01:39:37,749
Bonsoir, old thing

1433
01:39:37,840 --> 01:39:39,319
Cheerio, chin-chin

1434
01:39:39,400 --> 01:39:43,757
Napoo, toodle-oo, goodbye-ee

1435
01:39:43,880 --> 01:39:46,394
(ALL CH EERING)

1436
01:39:46,920 --> 01:39:48,478
(BLOGGS CH UCKLING)

1437
01:40:06,120 --> 01:40:07,599
(DAVID CHUCKLES TEARFULLY)

1438
01:40:14,240 --> 01:40:16,071
There's something
I have to say.

1439
01:40:17,040 --> 01:40:18,314
(CHUCKLES)

1440
01:40:19,560 --> 01:40:22,677
I want you to know what a
difference you've made to my life.

1441
01:40:25,280 --> 01:40:27,271
It's not always been
easy for me.

1442
01:40:29,960 --> 01:40:34,954
Every time I come here,
I go away stronger.

1443
01:40:36,120 --> 01:40:38,475
And it's not because
you're worse off than me.

1444
01:40:38,560 --> 01:40:40,312
No, no, no.

1445
01:40:43,760 --> 01:40:45,751
It's who you are, Robin.

1446
01:40:46,920 --> 01:40:49,718
Or who you've turned yourself into.
God knows how.

1447
01:40:52,520 --> 01:40:54,112
Thank you, Col.

1448
01:40:56,360 --> 01:40:57,998
I'm gonna miss you.

1449
01:41:04,240 --> 01:41:05,639
Robin.

1450
01:41:21,480 --> 01:41:22,913
I'm sorry.

1451
01:41:39,800 --> 01:41:40,915
Darling.

1452
01:41:46,800 --> 01:41:48,438
That's enough.

1453
01:42:03,760 --> 01:42:05,159
Yes.

1454
01:42:15,120 --> 01:42:17,350
I expect
you know this, but,

1455
01:42:24,640 --> 01:42:26,631
just in case...

1456
01:42:30,920 --> 01:42:33,832
No one could have loved you
as much as I've loved you.

1457
01:42:43,280 --> 01:42:44,713
I know.

1458
01:42:51,960 --> 01:42:53,359
My love.

1459
01:42:57,640 --> 01:42:59,039
And my life.

1460
01:43:08,400 --> 01:43:10,356
Me, too, Robin.

1461
01:43:13,520 --> 01:43:14,873
My love.

1462
01:43:17,400 --> 01:43:18,799
My life.

1463
01:43:44,920 --> 01:43:47,036
(LINE RINGING)

1464
01:43:56,320 --> 01:43:57,992
(RECEIVER CLICKS)

1465
01:43:59,280 --> 01:44:00,679
Clem.

1466
01:44:01,320 --> 01:44:02,719
DR. AITKEN: Hello, Robin.

1467
01:44:04,920 --> 01:44:06,319
It's time.

1468
01:44:08,000 --> 01:44:09,399
All right.

1469
01:44:10,760 --> 01:44:12,751
When?
Today.

1470
01:44:15,760 --> 01:44:17,159
Now.

1471
01:44:17,960 --> 01:44:20,793
I'll be with you at 11:30.

1472
01:44:22,160 --> 01:44:23,388
(LAUGHS)

1473
01:44:25,920 --> 01:44:28,388
It's like a military op, eh?

1474
01:44:29,440 --> 01:44:32,512
You can count on me.
Synchronize watches.

1475
01:44:34,880 --> 01:44:36,359
I'll be there.

1476
01:44:38,440 --> 01:44:40,078
Thank you, Clem.

1477
01:44:41,960 --> 01:44:43,359
See you soon.

1478
01:44:43,680 --> 01:44:45,033
(LINE DISCONNECTS)

1479
01:44:46,320 --> 01:44:47,878
(BUZZER SOUNDS)

1480
01:45:06,440 --> 01:45:08,078
Get Jonathan.

1481
01:45:11,520 --> 01:45:12,873
Jonathan.

1482
01:45:36,080 --> 01:45:40,232
I need you both to listen
very, very carefully.

1483
01:45:43,720 --> 01:45:45,711
Just before 11:30,

1484
01:45:48,080 --> 01:45:50,071
you're to leave the house.

1485
01:45:55,640 --> 01:45:57,631
And you're to come back

1486
01:46:01,520 --> 01:46:03,511
at 12:00 on the button.

1487
01:46:05,800 --> 01:46:07,233
DIANA: Okay.

1488
01:46:08,360 --> 01:46:10,590
Promise me
I'll have time to say goodbye.

1489
01:46:13,400 --> 01:46:15,391
ROBIN: Yes, there'll be time.

1490
01:46:18,240 --> 01:46:20,435
Hello. I haven't
seen you in a while.

1491
01:46:20,560 --> 01:46:22,278
So what can I get you all today?

1492
01:46:23,040 --> 01:46:25,474
JONATHAN:
I'm fine, thanks. Mum?

1493
01:46:57,160 --> 01:46:58,798
I'm still here.

1494
01:47:01,560 --> 01:47:03,551
You go first, Jonathan.

1495
01:47:20,240 --> 01:47:21,832
Bye, Dad.

1496
01:47:27,440 --> 01:47:29,078
I love you.

1497
01:47:31,160 --> 01:47:32,798
My own son.

1498
01:47:37,760 --> 01:47:39,478
My boy.

1499
01:47:47,000 --> 01:47:50,072
You have given me
more than you can ever know.

1500
01:48:18,920 --> 01:48:23,516
Now, I don't have
a farewell speech.

1501
01:48:24,720 --> 01:48:26,711
You don't mind, do you?

1502
01:48:35,200 --> 01:48:36,633
No.

1503
01:48:40,800 --> 01:48:42,791
You've given me
a wonderful life.

1504
01:48:47,840 --> 01:48:50,638
It wasn't quite
what you expected.

1505
01:48:50,720 --> 01:48:52,551
(CHUCKLES) No.

1506
01:48:57,640 --> 01:48:59,153
No, nor me.

1507
01:49:25,600 --> 01:49:27,238
Thank you.

1508
01:49:28,320 --> 01:49:29,912
For choosing to live.

1509
01:49:38,560 --> 01:49:39,959
(INAUDIBLE)

1510
01:51:00,560 --> 01:51:02,118
(ROMANTIC MUSIC PLAYING)

1511
01:52:00,200 --> 01:52:01,235
(INAUDIBLE)

